<HEAD>Judge Temporarily Halts Logging Near Spotted Owl Nests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY CARPENTER HALE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A federal judge Wednesday temporarily halted logging on five timber tracts that is being contested by conservationists seeking to preserve the northern spotted owl in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Helen </PERSON> <PERSON> Frye </PERSON>'s temporary restraining order came in response to a motion filed Tuesday by environmental groups fighting the federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>'s plans to log mature forests near spotted owl nests. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Rivers </PERSON>, acting <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> state </ORGANIZATION> director, said its district representatives had been told to notify logging companies to cease operations as soon as possible. A sixth tract affected by the judge's order has not yet been awarded. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>, in reckless disregard for the spotted owl, selected these six timber sales as a target of opportunity to make their point through chainsaw justice,'' said <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Wood </PERSON> of the <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Natural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, one of the plaintiffs. Rivers would not comment on <PERSON> Wood </PERSON>'s remarks. Meanwhile, in <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION>, nine conservation groups sued the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> Wednesday to try to stop logging on publicly owned stands of old-growth timber that are habitat for the northern spotted owl. The environmental groups contend a <ORGANIZATION> Forest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> plan for spotted owls does n't protect the species. The plan, approved in December, said 374,000 acres of mature and old-growth timber in 13 national forests in the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION> should be designated as owl habitat. That is in addition to the wilderness areas and other tracts protected from logging. The northern spotted owl lives in the remnants of the <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northwest </LOCATION>'s ancient old-growth forests. The Fish and <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> is being challenged in court over its 1987 refusal to designate the owl a threatened or endangered species. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> earlier this month lifted an injunction it earlier imposed on cutting timber near spotted owl nests on <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> land in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>. The appeals court sent the case back to <PERSON> Frye </PERSON>'s court. A request to reinstate the injunction is pending before <PERSON> Frye </PERSON>. On Wednesday, <PERSON> Frye </PERSON> set a Feb. 17 hearing on that motion. In response to the appeals court's injunction, the <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Land </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION> cut its projected timber harvest on the former <ORGANIZATION> Oregon </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Railroad lands it manages in western <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION> by about 25 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> BLM </ORGANIZATION> announced the six timber tracts after the injunction was lifted.
