<HEAD>U.S. Subway Vigilantes To Go Ahead With London Chapter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Guardian Angels say that with the backing of the director of two <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Bronson </PERSON> movies and a <LOCATION> British </LOCATION> businessman they will start training recruits in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> next week _ despite official opposition. <PERSON> Curtis </PERSON> <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON>, leader of the New York-based group that wants to send civilian patrols into the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> Underground, had threatened to abandon the plan unless the crime-fighting group could find training space. He said police and some government officials had `` dug their heels in'' and refused to allow the <ORGANIZATION> Angels </ORGANIZATION> to train in public places. Police and lawmakers have said law enforcement on the subways should be left to professionals, not civilians. After discussing the Angels' plight on a highly popular <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> television talk show, <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON> said Wednesday that he had received two offers of help _ from <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON>, owner of a chain of public recital halls throughout <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, and from director <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> Winner </PERSON>. Winner directed `` Death Wish'' and `` Death Wish II'', both starring <PERSON> Bronson </PERSON> as a tough vigilante who settles the score with cold-blooded criminals. <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON> said <PERSON> Fagan </PERSON> offered the Angels the use of a hall evenings `` with no strings attached'' for a three-month training course and Winner guaranteed that if there were any problems, he would pay for a training facility. `` It gives us a mandate to continue,'' <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON> said. The Guardian Angels had also received hundreds of calls from people who offered gardens, rooms, attics and backyards for training, <PERSON> Sliwa </PERSON> said. He said 60 young people, one-third of them women, had applied to become <PERSON> Angels </PERSON> and would on Monday begin a training program in basic self-defense, first aid, performing citizens arrests and `` human relations.'' `` We're going to give it a go for the three months of training, and hopefully by early May be able to produce a Guardian Angel unit of young men and young women from the greater <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> area to go down into the Underground and give you a permanent, regular presence of Guardian Angels,'' he said. Supporters of the Angels say a sharp rise in assaults and robberies in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s subway system indicate the 2.2 million passengers who use it every day ca n't be protected without deploying many more uniformed police. The Guardian Angels, who turn 10 years old on Monday, became famous for patroling <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s subways and have branched out into 60 cities in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>.
