<HEAD>Laurel Trip To Marcos Bedside A Bid To Boost Dying Political Fortunes</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: SUBS lead to FIX typo, 6th graf to CORRECT style on `persuade.'
Picks up 7th pvs, `The government ...' ^AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT H. REID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vice President <PERSON> Salvador </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON>'s visit to <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' bedside in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> is widely seen as a bid to revive his dying political fortunes and angle for right-wing support as he seeks the presidency. On Saturday, <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> returned from <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION> carrying what he said were secret messages from the ailing <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> for President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> appealed to Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s `` Christian values'' to allow the ex-president to come home to die. But Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> refused to see <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON>, reflecting the low esteem in which she holds the vice president. Furthermore, many political commentators accused Laurel of `` grandstanding'' in the sensitive national question of whether to allow the 71-year-old <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return from exile in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>. `` The nakedness of <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION>'s ambitions leaves little room for respect,'' wrote The <ORGANIZATION> Manila </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION>. `` It has become clear that the man is so obsessed with winning power that he would grab at straws to support his bid.'' Laurel has so little influence with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> that it seemed virtually impossible that he would be able to persuade her to relent and allow <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to return home. The government says <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> and his associates embezzled up to $ 10 billion during his 20-year rule and Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has refused to discuss his return until he gives back the money. Several congressmen and political commentators believe <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> intended through the trip to ingratiate himself with <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' followers, especially those in northern <LOCATION> Luzon </LOCATION> island, and use them as a base of support in the 1992 presidential campaign Inheriting the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> mantle would enable <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> to outflank other potential center-right candidates, such as Sen. <PERSON> Juan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ponce </PERSON> <PERSON> Enrile </PERSON>, who might appeal to those who would not support Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> or anyone seen as her favored candidate. Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> has said she will not seek re-election. `` With the demise of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>, the so-called ` solid north' is in need of someone to rally around,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Florencio </PERSON> <PERSON> Abad </PERSON>. The 60-year-old Laurel would seem an ideal `` reconciliation candidate'' to bring together a nation still deeply divided three years after <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> was ousted in a popular uprising. Laurel announced he would run for president against <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> in 1985, but stepped aside under pressure to become Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>'s running mate A member of an elite political clan, <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> maintains links to the business community and the military. But a series of political blunders has reinforced his deeply entrenched public image as an opportunist. After a bloody August 1987 coup attempt, <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION> traveled to military bases, ostensibly to investigate soldiers' complaints. Before the television cameras, he would shout, `` Do you want Communists out of government?'' That brought cheers from the troops but contempt from more liberal-minded urban voters, who joked that <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON> was becoming a `` Filipino <PERSON> McCarthy </PERSON>.'' In September 1987, he resigned as foreign secretary, citing widespread differences with Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> on the 20-year-old Communist insurgency and other issues. A year later, he demanded she resign and call new elections, but she refused. Instead of winning sympathy by his moves, <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION>'s popularity plunged. <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> newspapers and television stations rarely report his activities and his speeches draw only modest audiences. Despite Laurel's personal campaigning, his nephew, <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Laurel </PERSON>, was defeated in the January 1988 race for governor of <LOCATION> Batangas </LOCATION> province, the Laurel family stronghold. Since formally breaking with the administration in August, <ORGANIZATION> Laurel </ORGANIZATION>'s attempt to organize a broad-based opposition movement have faltered. He complained last year to foreign reporters that he was virtually ignored by the media. His principal public forum in the capital has been occasional interviews by Tagalog-language radio stations. `` It would be a gross understatement to say that <PERSON> Doy </PERSON> has an image problem,'' wrote columnist <PERSON> Ed </PERSON> <PERSON> Olaguer </PERSON>, referring to Laurel by his nickname.
