<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s $ 81 billion plan to modernize and clean up nuclear weapons plants over 20 years would save the nation's production of war devices but fail to remove all environmental hazards, the head of <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> says. `` Modernization activities would essentially be completed by 2010, and the nation would have a revitalized weapons complex,'' Comptroller General <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON> told a congressional hearing Wednesday. `` However, problems in the environmental area would still be with us.'' <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON> told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> it would take up to $ 155 billion over 30 years to modernize the industry, clean up closed plants and protect the environment from radioactive contamination. Material for nuclear weapons is produced at reactors and other facilities in a dozen states, but has effectively stopped because of safety concerns at reactor sites in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION>. Energy officials told another congressional committee last week they hope to get the tritium-producing reactor at the <LOCATION> Savannah </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> site in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Carolina </LOCATION> back in operation before the end of the year, but may not be able to do it that soon. The reactor has been out of operation since August when an unexplained power surge caused it to shut down and other potential hazards were discovered. The Energy Department, in an unsigned statement submitted to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee, said the department `` has produced and maintained an effective nuclear deterrent that is the cornerstone of our national defense.'' But the department acknowledged that past decisions have focused on meeting short-term national security needs rather than environmental and safety concerns. It said the practice at many of the facilities of dumping waste into open, unlined pits and ponds has led to `` a major challenge in restoring the soil and groundwater underlying some inactive waste sites.'' <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON>, in his testimony, said, `` In our opinion, the -LRB- department's -RRB- plan does not adequately address the cleanup of existing facilities and decontamination of facilities as they are retired from service.'' He said if problems affecting the nuclear complex are not addressed soon, `` the country's ability to produce and maintain a nuclear weapons arsenal is in serious jeopardy.'' <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON> said the major difference between his congressional watchdog agency's estimate of $ 105 billion to $ 155 billion and the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> estimate of $ 81 billion to modernize and clean up the plants is over how much it will take to decontaminate and protect the environment. <PERSON> Bowsher </PERSON> said the nuclear weapons complex is `` one of the more potentially dangerous industrial operations in the world'' and some nuclear production sites may be `` irreversibly contaminated.'' He said <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> plans to spend $ 315 million in fiscal 1990 on environmental cleanup represent `` only a small down payment'' on the $ 40 billion to $ 70 billion needed.
