<SECOND>PM-Kabul-Mood,0712</SECOND>
<HEAD>Encircled Afghan Capital Calm _ At Least On The Surface</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SHARON HERBAUGH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KABUL, Afghanistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 In a courtyard where only enormous wooden and rusting beams keep the walls from collapsing, the money-changers ply their trade. In this sensitive and openly tolerated black market, the value of currency can change with a small gesture of the hand or inflection of the voice. Today there is no sign of panic. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> dollar is changing hands for 210 afghanis, compared to 238 a week ago when Soviet soldiers were still seen in full force. Now the Soviets are all but gone, and the money-changers say there's a feeling their departure will lead to peace and that the perenially warring Afghans will settle down to their traditional way of handling things _ by making a deal. Whether that's a realistic attitude remains to be seen, but the <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>'s departure is having a buoyant effect. `` We did n't need them here,'' said one money-changer, <PERSON> Mohammad </PERSON> <PERSON> Yahir </PERSON>. `` We have problems, but we can solve them ourselves, God willing. I think it will be OK.'' One by one, Soviet bases around this city of 2 million people have been handed over to Afghan government forces Several hundred Soviet soldiers are still hanging on to guard the <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> airport, but they are to leave by next week. The rest of the thousands of <ORGANIZATION> Red </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> troops who were around the capital three weeks ago are home or on their way, either in convoys heading up the snowy <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highway </LOCATION> to the Soviet border or on huge military transport planes. Moslem guerrillas have launched few rocket attacks on <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, and the government shelling of guerrilla hideouts in the mountains has tapered off. On the surface at least, <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION> is calm. The markets bustle with women clad in traditional chadris, the all-enveloping veil that cascades in pleats from a skullcap, with a coarse mesh panel over the eyes. Children slide down the icy hills and fly kites in the street. Smoke-belching buses and horn-blaring taxis jam the narrow streets. Carts filled with fresh bananas and oranges from neighboring <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and pomegranates and apples from other parts of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> mask for a few seconds the stench of impoverished humanity. On Chicken Street, the main venue for foreigners and the wealthy, merchants sell everything from centuries-old carpets and antique muskets to Swiss watches and German beer. `` Goods are still coming in. There is plenty of food and other goods. All you need is the money to pay,'' said a merchant who identified himself only as Tamoor. The Soviet armored personnel carriers that a few days ago stood at the end of Chicken Street are gone. In their place are Afghan soldiers, clutching a Soviet-designed Kalashnikov rifle in one hand and prayer beads in the other. Few signs remain of <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>'s nine-year military intervention except for the <LOCATION> Volga </LOCATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Moskvich </ORGANIZATION> cars, fur hats, vodka and <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> caviar _ which has nearly tripled in price since the final Soviet withdrawal started in early January. Afghans openly voice their hostility toward Soviets and look upon foreigners with suspicion. `` Where are you from?'' <PERSON> Qurban </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> asked a group of Westerners. `` <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>,'' one of them answered. `` Forgive me,'' <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> said, motioning the group inside his carpet shop. `` I thought you were Russian.'' For the city's 350,000 poor people, things are not so comfortable. A Soviet airlift and attacks on guerrillas blocking the <LOCATION> Salang </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Highway </LOCATION> have eased shortages of flour, but lines persist at the shacks where bread is sold. The poorest people survive on diets of bread, rice and tea. Heating oil and fuel are even scarcer, making a bitter winter even harder. A liter of gasoline sells on the black market for 175 to 500 afghanis -LRB- $ 3.20 to $ 9.10 at the official exchange rate -RRB-, compared to 30 afghanis -LRB- 55 cents at the official rate -RRB- for the scarce and tightly rationed government supplies. `` I had to walk seven kilometers -LRB- four miles -RRB- to work today,'' said a government interpreter. `` It's best to live near the trolley lines. They run on electricity.''
</TEXT>
