<HEAD>Survey Finds Tokyo's Ginza To Be World's Highest-Priced Street</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s glitzy commercial center, has become the most expensive street in the world, relegating <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>'s East 57th Street to second place, according to a survey. The rental survey was conducted by the <ORGANIZATION> Hirschfeld </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Companies </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-based </LOCATION> retail real-estate marketing firm, and released Wednesday. Although the <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION> edged East 57th Street out of the first-place spot it held last year, <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> thoroughfares still managed to garner four of the top 10 places. The survey found that retailers on the <LOCATION> Ginza </LOCATION> pay an average rent of $ 650 a square foot. The rest of the top 10 were: _ East 57th Street -LRB- $ 435 -RRB- _ Fifth Avenue between 50th and 59th streets -LRB- $ 375 -RRB- _ Madison Avenue between 62nd and 72nd streets -LRB- $ 335 -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Rodeo </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Drive </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Beverly </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hills </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> -LRB- $ 225 -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Nathan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Road </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> -LRB- $ 200 -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Bond </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> -LRB- $ 180 -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Rue </LOCATION> <LOCATION> de </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Faubourg </LOCATION> <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Honore </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Paris </LOCATION> -LRB- $ 175 -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Bloor </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Street </LOCATION> in <LOCATION> Toronto </LOCATION> -LRB- $ 150 -RRB- _ <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Avenue </LOCATION> between 57th and 60th streets -LRB- $ 150 -RRB-.
