<SECOND>PM-Obit-Piro,0256</SECOND>
<HEAD>High Society Dance Teacher Dead at 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> `` </PERSON> <PERSON> Killer </PERSON> <PERSON> Joe </PERSON><PERSON> '' </PERSON> <PERSON> Piro </PERSON>, the dancer who taught high society everything from the cha-cha to the hully-gully, has died of kidney disease at age 68. <PERSON> Piro </PERSON>, who got his nickname because he easily outlasted partners on the dance floor, died Tuesday at a hospital in <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION>. For decades, the short, sinewy dancer performed on stage and television, taught at his <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> studio and made nightly rounds of parties and clubs. Always a step ahead of fashion, <PERSON> Piro </PERSON> taught the mambo, the cha-cha and the merengue, then the twist, the frug, the frog and the watusi. His students included the <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> and Duchess of <LOCATION> Windsor </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Luci </PERSON> <PERSON> Baines </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, daughter of President <PERSON> Lyndon </PERSON> <PERSON> Johnson </PERSON>, not to mention other dancers such as <PERSON> Dame </PERSON> <PERSON> Margot </PERSON> <PERSON> Fonteyn </PERSON> and <PERSON> Ray </PERSON> <PERSON> Bolger </PERSON>. <PERSON> Piro </PERSON> was born in <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION>, the son of an Italian tailor. He said he took up dancing at a neighborhood social club to meet girls. He dropped out of school after eighth grade, working at construction jobs and plastics designing. Meanwhile, he kept winning <LOCATION> Harlem </LOCATION> dance contests, including the 1942 National Jitterbug Championship at the Harvest Moon Ball. After serving in the <ORGANIZATION> Coast </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION> during World War II, <PERSON> Piro </PERSON> entered and won dance contests at the Palladium so often, he said, they offered him $ 15 a week to teach dancing _ and stop competing. He is survived by his wife, <PERSON> Lucienne </PERSON>; a daughter, a stepson and two sisters.
