<FIRST>r i PM-Nicaragua-Asylum     02-09 0431</FIRST>
<SECOND>PM-Nicaragua-Asylum,0444</SECOND>
<HEAD>Gov't Allows Former Somoza Officers To Leave After Nearly 10 Years</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DORALISA PILARTE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After nearly a decade of political asylum in the <ORGANIZATION> Venezuelan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION>, two former high-ranking officers in the army of the ousted <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON> regime were permitted to leave and flew to <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>. Col. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> O. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> and Capt. <PERSON> Mario </PERSON> <PERSON> Guerra </PERSON> <PERSON> Palacios </PERSON> arrived in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> City Wednesday night aboard a commercial flight from <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>. They were greeted by a Venezuelan diplomat and taken to a nearby hotel. Diplomatic sources in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> the pair would remain in <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION> a few days and that they planned to seek political asylum in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The sources spoke on condition of anonymity. The two fled to the Venezuelan Embassy in July 1979, the same month the leftist <ORGANIZATION> Sandinista </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Liberation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Front </ORGANIZATION> took power after a popular uprising ousted President <PERSON> Anastasio </PERSON> <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON>, 62, and <LOCATION> Guerra </LOCATION>, 42, were members of the now-disbanded <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guard </ORGANIZATION>, as the army was known under <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>. Known as `` The Ranger'' because of his <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> military training, <PERSON> Gutierrez </PERSON> was one of <PERSON> Somoza </PERSON>'s trusted officers. He had suffered two heart attacks in confinement, and said in a 1986 interview that the only way out was if the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> `` comes in and wipes these Communists out. `` Either that, or we will end up dying here,'' he had said. <PERSON> Guerra </PERSON> kept himself busy by studying radio and television repair, and completed a correspondence course in electronics in 1986. In <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>, the opposition newspaper <ORGANIZATION> La </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Prensa </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday quoted unidentified sources as saying the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> gave the two a one-year `` exit permit'' instead of the customary safe-conduct pass. Repeated telephone calls to the <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> and the Venezuelan Embassy in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> went unanswered. Reporters were kept away from several Venezuelan diplomats gathered at <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION>'s <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Sandino </PERSON> International Airport before the pair left. Allowing the officers to leave was seen as a gesture of goodwill toward the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> by the Sandinista government, which is trying to cope with a rapidly deteriorating economy. Inflation reached 20,000 percent in 1988. The government has blamed economic problems on eight years of war with the U.S.-backed Contra rebels; Hurricane Joan, which struck the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> coast last October; and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade embargo since 1985. President <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> is scheduled to attend a summit of <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> presidents next week in <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>. The meeting, postponed many times, was called under a regional peace plan signed by <PERSON> Ortega </PERSON> and the presidents of <LOCATION> El </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Salvador </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Honduras </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Guatemala </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Costa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Rica </LOCATION> in August 1987.
</TEXT>
