<HEAD>Famed Conductor Asks For Reprieve From Contract Due To Health</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CAROL J. WILLIAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BERLIN (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Famed conductor <PERSON> Herbert </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> has asked for a reprieve from his contract with the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Philharmonic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> because of failing health, officials said today. The 80-year-old conductor wrote <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> culture authorities that he is unable to keep up with the pace demanded by his contract and wants to rest at his home near <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Austria </LOCATION>. `` He needs to reduce his workload and has submitted the recommendations of three doctors to that effect,'' said <PERSON> Ludwig </PERSON> <PERSON> von </PERSON> <PERSON> Pufendorf </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> secretary for cultural affairs. <PERSON> Pufendorf </PERSON> said <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>'s request was `` nothing dramatic'' because the Austrian conductor has been ill for years. But with the letter, <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> conceded for the first time that his ability to conduct has been affected by a stroke, failing vision, circulatory problems and at least five operations he has undergone in the last 12 years. <PERSON> Pufendorf </PERSON> said <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>'s obligations with the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Symphony </LOCATION> had been reduced to 6 concerts per year from 12 as earlier was required. <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> has conducted the <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> Philharmonic since 1954 and holds the honorary title of lifetime director. He is also lifetime director of <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Friends </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Music </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> and has regularly conducted the <ORGANIZATION> Vienna </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Opera </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> Salzburg </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Lucerne </LOCATION> music festivals. <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> underwent a nine-hour operation in 1976 and had surgery again in 1979. He has been visibly hindered since a 1983 operation on his spinal column and two later operations to remove tumors. He has required a supporting chair behind the conducting pulpit for more than a year and is reported by orchestra members to be so far-sighted that he can not read music anymore and conducts from memory. He also suffers from a hearing problem. <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON> asked in the letter to <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION> cultural affairs senator <PERSON> Volker </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassemer </PERSON> for a break from his concert duties, noting he continues to suffer circulatory problems as a result of the stroke and influenza contracted last year. `` <PERSON> Karajan </PERSON>'s health is not what it used to be,'' <PERSON> Hassemer </PERSON> said. `` His life is a heroic exertion against illness and pain,'' a <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> music critic commented.
