<HEAD>Asher Edelman's Brother Indicted In Alleged Tax Scam</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN M. DOYLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> financier and a <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> businessman have been indicted for allegedly faking more than $ 38 billion in trades in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government securities in a massive tax fraud scheme. `` There were no real transactions. It was all pieces of paper going back and forth,'' <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Benito </PERSON> <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> said Wednesday. `` It was an entirely fictitious operation.'' <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> said the case, which allegedly involved $ 511 million in illegal tax writeoffs, was at least as large as any previous case of its type. <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, 43, of Rye, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Bernhard </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Manko </PERSON>, 48, of <LOCATION> Lighthouse </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Point </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Fla. </LOCATION>, were charged with conspiracy to defraud the <ORGANIZATION> Internal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Revenue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> and numerous counts of making false statements to the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> or aiding others to do so. <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, the brother of prominent takeover strategist <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON>, issued a statement calling the charges `` unfounded, unfair and unjust.'' `` I am confident that I will be completely vindicated by the jury that will hear my case,'' he said. <PERSON> Manko </PERSON>'s lawyer, <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON> <PERSON> Chepiga </PERSON>, said she had n't yet reviewed the indictment but `` based on what has come to our attention during this long investigation, we believe Mr. <PERSON> Manko </PERSON> will be entirely vindicated.'' The investors were unwitting participants in the scheme and are n't under investigation, <PERSON> Romano </PERSON> said, although `` they may have to undergo civil audits'' to determine whether they owe back taxes. The investors include billionaire <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Kluge </PERSON>, the chairman of <ORGANIZATION> Metromedia </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Brien </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Kluge </PERSON>, confirmed his client and <PERSON> Kluge </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Patricia </PERSON>, had invested in two Edelman-Manko partnerships He said <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> audits of the partnerships `` have been going on for years'' and that a settlement with all the partners to cover back taxes was being implemented. Among other investors listed in the indictment was a <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>. Prosecutors would not confirm if it was the late fashion designer, and calls to a spokesman for <PERSON> Ellis </PERSON>'s company were not returned. <PERSON> Asher </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> was not implicated in the alleged scheme. Through a spokeswoman, <PERSON> Maureen </PERSON> <PERSON> Connelly </PERSON>, he issued a statement: `` This is a distressing and difficult time for our family. I will do everything in my power to assist my brother because I do not believe he would engage in any unlawful activity.'' <PERSON> Jon </PERSON> <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> and <PERSON> Manko </PERSON> were accused of creating more than $ 38 billion in `` pre-arranged, rigged and fraudulent'' transactions in government securities to generate losses for investors in numerous limited partnerships, which the investors could write off against their taxes. The scheme involved at least 15 partnerships between 1982 and 1986, the indictment charges. Both <PERSON> Manko </PERSON> and <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> were charged with conspiracy, which carries a maximum penalty of five years in prison and a $ 10,000 fine. <PERSON> Manko </PERSON> was charged with 24 false statement counts and <PERSON> Edelman </PERSON> was charged with 25 similar counts, each of which carries up to three years in prison and a $ 5,000 fine. The pair also was accused of creating false trading and financing confirmations, causing the distribution of fraudulent sales literature and misleading lawyers who prepared offering materials and signed tax opinion letters for some of the limited partnerships.
