<HEAD>Walesa Asks Workers Not To Strike While Negotiations Continue</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout with Walesa appealing to workers not to strike,
opposition-government talks resume, details, minor editing. No pickup.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Coal miners at <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s largest power plant suspended a three-day strike today and <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> appealed to workers not to strike while he tries to negotiate Solidarity's reinstatement `` Give a chance to the round table,'' The chairman of the free trade union movement said in an interview on state radio just hours after the miners ended the stoppage that had threatened to shut down the Belchatow plant's generators. `` <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> is appealing for a chance for the round table. We have been waiting for so many years, we can wait a few days more,'' he said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> had dispatched an envoy to help settle the dispute. He joined a working group on trade union issues that began talks today as part of historic `` round table'' talks between the opposition and government that opened Monday and are expected to last up to six weeks. `` Belchatow is just another proof that we should reach agreement on the most important things as soon as possible, and restore the organization called Solidarity,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said in the radio interview. The decision to suspend the strike at <LOCATION> Belchatow </LOCATION> until Feb. 28 followed a visit to the mine 90 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> by an envoy for <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> and management's agreement to provide most of the pay raise sought by strikers, state radio reported. The strike had reduced coal supplies at Belchatow to about two days' reserves. The strip mine at the complex fuels the plant's generators, which produce one-fifth of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s electricity State radio said management raised pay by $ 41 a month, compared to the $ 59 monthly raise sought by the 4,000 strikers. On average, workers at the plant earn $ 145 monthly. Government spokesman <PERSON> Jerzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Urban </PERSON> had on Wednesday had accused <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s envoy, <PERSON> Aloyzy </PERSON> <PERSON> Pietrzyk </PERSON>, of encouraging the strike at a rally attended by thousands of workers rather than trying to ease it. `` I must express decisive anxiety for the sense of the round table talks and chances for agreement. Agreement is not possible under strike pressure,'' Urban said. Today's working group was co-chaired by <PERSON> Tadeusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Mazowiecki </PERSON>, a top Solidarity adviser, <PERSON> Romuald </PERSON> <PERSON> Sosnowski </PERSON>, deputy chairman of the official trade union alliance OPZZ and <PERSON> Aleksander </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwasniewski </PERSON>, minister of sports and tourism. Solidarity hopes the negotiations will culminate in the restoration of its legal status after a seven-year ban. The government seeks to persuade its leaders to join parliament as a minority party. The Polish economy, beset by a $ 39 billion foreign debt, is in ruins. There are chronic shortages of basic goods and supplies, inflation was at 60 percent last year, and the declining value of real wages has produced increased worker unrest, including 39 strikes last month. Interior Minister Gen. <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszcak </PERSON> first proposed the negotiations in August during the country's worst labor unrest since the authorities crushed Solidarity in a December 1981 military crackdown. The only independent labor movement ever allowed in the Soviet bloc was outlawed the following year. The government has sought the promise of a two-year strike moratorium in return for reinstatement of Solidarity. But <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, while acknowledging that strikes do n't help the economy, insists that workers have the right to strike over poor pay and working conditions. He has repeatedly warned Communist authorities of the potential of further unrest if economic and politial reforms are not implemented quickly. State television said 4,000 of the 12,500 workers at the Belchatow plant were on strike. The <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> put the number at 8,000. Signs of labor tension appeared elsewhere in the country today. Workers at the coke department of the <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> steel mill near <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> have been refusing since Feb. 1 to work overtime, Solidarity spokesmen reported. Last year, riot police broke up a strike at the plant, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s largest steel mill. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> was planning to travel to <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> later today to talk with workers from <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>.
