<TEXT>
 The family of a <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> recruit who panicked and drowned during rescue training has filed a $ 20 million claim against the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>. The death in March of <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>, 19, of <LOCATION> Appleton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wis. </LOCATION>, led to charges against instructors and reform of training practices at the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rescue </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Swimmer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> here. The claim accuses the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> of negligence in allowing <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON> back into the class after he had been diagnosed as having a phobia about being held under water. It also charges the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> of intentionally inflicting emotional distress on the family by first reporting that <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s death was an accident. The family, dissatisfied with the initial report, got help from congressmen in getting an investigation that led to charges. <PERSON> Ross </PERSON> <PERSON> Goodman </PERSON>, an attorney for <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>'s family, said the claim was sent Wednesday to the commander of the Naval Air Station in <LOCATION> Pensacola </LOCATION>. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> has six months to respond. If it does not respond, the family can file a lawsuit, he said. Cmdr. <PERSON> Dennis </PERSON> <PERSON> Hessler </PERSON> said the claim would be forwarded to the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> legal services office on the base. He would not comment further. Witnesses said <PERSON> Mirecki </PERSON>, who had a phobia about being held under water, was dragged back in despite his pleas to quit the training. A pathologist concluded that he was literally scared to death, suffering heart failure and drowning. An instructor was convicted by court-martial of negligent homicide. Four other instructors received administrative punishments of fines or demotions. The officer in charge was acquitted of dereliction of duty. As a result of the case, instructors are no longer allowed to come into physical contact with students and must immediately cease drilling trainees who panic, ask to quit or show signs of excessive fatigue, the <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION> said.
