<HEAD>Affirmative Action Promise Releases State Money For Symphony</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF HOLYFIELD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LANSING, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Legislators freed $ 1.25 million for the ailing <ORGANIZATION> Detroit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Symphony </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orchestra </ORGANIZATION> after it pledged to try to hire more black musicians. The 100-member orchestra has only one black musician, even though its home city is two-thirds black, and until recently has n't tried to recruit more, its chairman, <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> <PERSON> Jr. </PERSON>, said at a legislative hearing Wednesday. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said he made no specific promise to hire a black musician but that he hoped the orchestra would hire one before the end of the year. Last year, the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> appropriated $ 2.5 million to help the financially struggling orchestra. The orchestra got half the money immediately, but lawmakers reserved the rest until they reviewed its efforts to hire minorities and solve its financial problems. On Wednesday, an appropriations subcommittee freed the rest of the money on a unanimous vote. `` I'm convinced major change has taken place and will continue to take place in the orchestra,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Morris </PERSON> <PERSON> Hood </PERSON>, who sharply criticized the orchestra's record on hiring blacks in a meeting last week. <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said that the orchestra would be `` out of business'' without the money. `` One is we ca n't afford to lose this money. Secondly, if we were to be denied this money, the reason would be we did n't live up to affirmative action goals,'' he said. `` I could n't go to any corporation or individual and say, ` Please keep us in business, the state just cut off our water because we're racist.''' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said symphony executives were developing a five-year plan to take care of the money problems. But hiring more blacks could be more difficult because there are relatively few black classical musicians, the symphony has only about a half-dozen openings each year and it uses a blind audition in which musicians are screened from the judges when they play, he said. As many as 100 musicians apply for each opening in the symphony and only one to three are black, <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. Musicians earn about $ 50,000 a year. `` This is the big leagues and every kid on the sandlot wants to play in the major leagues and <LOCATION> Detroit </LOCATION> is one of those,'' he said. `` In the music world, this is a high-paying, glamorous job.''
