nd rural areas far from the big tourist hotels on the north coast. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> and <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> signed a peace accord in August in an attempt to prevent violence, but throughout the campaign they accused each other of breaching it. The charismatic <PERSON> Manley </PERSON>, 64, educated at the <ORGANIZATION> London </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, was prime minister from 1972 to 1980. He has projected a moderate, pro-U.S. image in contrast to his previous far-left leadership. <PERSON> Manley </PERSON> said he would restore relations with neighboring communist <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> during his first year in office but only on a restricted and formal basis. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON> broke relations with <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> upon taking office in 1980. <PERSON> Seaga </PERSON>, 58, who was born in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> and educated at <ORGANIZATION> Harvard </ORGANIZATION>, has been one of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>' closest allies in the <LOCATION> Caribbean </LOCATION>. He has helped restore <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s battered economy, but higher taxes and devaluation of the Jamaican dollar have cut deeply into the purchasing power of most wage earners and the standard of living of <LOCATION> Jamaica </LOCATION>'s 2.4 million people has continued to fall.
