<HEAD>U.S. Sales to Europe May Reach Level of Imports</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Sales by Americans to 12 West European countries will reach the level of imports by the end of this year if present trends continue, a <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said Thursday. `` That's not a prediction, it's a projection,'' <PERSON> Franklin </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Vargo </PERSON>, deputy assistant secretary for <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>, told reporters. He told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Community </ORGANIZATION> rose more than 25 percent last year while <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports rose 5 percent, changes which cut the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> trade deficit with the community to $ 13 billion from $ 24 billion in 1987. Another year of those trends and the deficit will disappear, he said. He pointed out that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies and their affiliates sold more than $ 600 billion worth of goods to the 12 countries last year, three times as much as to <LOCATION> Canada </LOCATION> and four times as much as to <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. For many years after World War II, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> exports to western <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> exceeded imports. In recent years, that trend has reversed. The 12 countries in the community are <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> France </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Italy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Denmark </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ireland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Belgium </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Holland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Luxembourg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Spain </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Greece </LOCATION>. They are now trying to turn their association into a single market, almost as integrated as the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, by the end of 1992. Some Americans see that movement as a threat of a `` Fortress <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION>'' which would keep out <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> goods. `` On balance 1992 should benefit the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Vargo </PERSON> told the committee. He said faster growth should furnish a better market for <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> goods. But he said there are many problems remaining, especially in the common standards being set by the 12 governments for imported products and the possibility that tests of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> products to see that they meet those standards will be required on European soil. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Swain </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Small </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>'s chief counsel for advocacy, urged <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> companies to set up a subsidiary in one of the 12 countries. `` The consensus is that the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> single internal market will materialize, if not by 1992, then shortly thereafter,'' he said in testimony for the committee. `` Establishing a subsidiary in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> would be the safest option, although it also could be the costliest choice initially,'' he said.
