<FIRST>r a AM-ABA-Guardianship     02-09 0468</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-ABA-Guardianship,0480</SECOND>
<HEAD>ABA Adopts Guardianship Reform Plan in Response to AP Series</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DENVER (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> has adopted a plan to overhaul the nation's guardianship system for the elderly by tightening judicial procedures, requiring more accountability and educating judges and guardians. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Delegates </ORGANIZATION>, on a voice vote Tuesday, approved the reforms drafted by guardianship experts last summer in response to an <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> series, said <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> on Legal Problems of the Elderly. The AP report, `` Guardianship of the Elderly: An Ailing System,'' found widespread abuse through guardianship, the court-administrated system designed to protect the elderly. Ms. <PERSON> Coleman </PERSON> said that the <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> policy will be used to help states draft guardianship reforms as well as generate education requirements for judges and those who serve as guardians of the elderly. By itself, it will not change guardianship laws. `` People looking to make changes can use what is now <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> policy as a platform for measuring change,'' she said. `` In daily practice, lawyers and judges could use it as a basis for making changes in their courts.'' The House of Delegates, the policy-making body for the nation's largest lawyers' organization, recommended a broad range of changes, from new court procedures to stricter standards for judges, attorneys and guardians The package also encouraged the legal system to rely more on alternatives to guardianship when appropriate. Under guardianship, old people determined to be incompetent by a court can lose most of their rights, such as deciding where they will live, how they'll spend their money and what kind of medical care they'll receive. The <ORGANIZATION> ABA </ORGANIZATION> delegates called for reforms to make the guardianship process more understandable to the elderly, including easy-to-read court petitions and better training for court officers. The package also called for stricter criteria for placing people under guardianship and closer scrutiny of the wards and their finances once they are placed under guardianship. The original proposal had included mandatory legal representation for those facing guardianship and a set of rules for attorneys representing guardians and those facing guardianship. Those sections were dropped at the urging of members of the bar's Section on <ORGANIZATION> Real </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Property </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Probate </ORGANIZATION> and Trust, who called for further study. The recommendation came out of a national conference on guardianship last July called in response to the 1987 AP investigation, which looked at the guardianship system in all 50 states and found that many old people are placed under guardianship without legal counsel, often without a day in court. Once the elderly are placed under guardianship, the courts often lost track of them, leaving the wards and their money prey to abuse. AP reporters found many instances of money misspent and the elderly mistreated. The series received the bar association's Silver Gavel Award in 1988.
</TEXT>
