<HEAD>Wild Golden Eagle Dies After Clinging To Life More Than Week</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOPKINSVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A wild golden eagle that had clung to life for more than a week after being shot with buckshot died Thursday, a veterinarian said. `` He was a very magnificent animal, and it's just a shame,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Loran </PERSON> <PERSON> Wagoner </PERSON>, a partner at the <ORGANIZATION> Skyline </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Animal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Clinic </ORGANIZATION> who had performed emergency surgery on the bird Tuesday. `` Words just ca n't express how you feel when you put all the effort into it and they die. The eagle, a 10-pound adult male with a 6-foot wingspan, was discovered Tuesday by state <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> workers near <LOCATION> Sharon </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Grove </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Kentucky </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Wagoner </PERSON> said it apparently had been shot about a week earlier and was suffering from malnutrition. He and three other veterinarians installed intramedullary pins to hold the eagle's broken bones together and were trying to restore the enfeebled bird's strength sufficiently to transfer it to the <LOCATION> Louisville </LOCATION> Zoo for full recovery. `` The surgery went very successfully, and the bird fully recovered from the anesthetic,'' <PERSON> Wagoner </PERSON> said. `` In fact, during the day yesterday, the bird continually got stronger. By yesterday afternoon, he was occasionally striking at the hand of the person that was feeding him.'' However, <PERSON> Wagoner </PERSON> said when he came to feed the bird about 9:30 p.m. Wednesday night, `` I noticed what seemed to be neurological signs developing. I called the veterinarian at the <ORGANIZATION> Louisville </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Zoo </ORGANIZATION>, and he was n't sure if this was the case. It was just a wait-and-see type of thing.'' The bird died a few hours later. Shooting a golden eagle or a bald eagle carries a federal penalty of up to a $ 100,000 fine or one year in prison. The state <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Wildlife </ORGANIZATION> has asked for the public's help in identifying the shooter.
