<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A former state highway official agreed to testify against others and then changed his plea Thursday to guilty to federal charges of extortion and filing false income tax returns, prosecutors said. <PERSON> Sam </PERSON> <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON> resigned in December as one of the three members of the <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> in the face of the impending charges. Assistant <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Attorney <PERSON> Ruth </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> told <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> that <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON> had helped in the investigation of other unspecified cases and his `` continued cooperation will include testimony before grand juries and at trials.'' <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> said <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON>'s sentencing would be scheduled later on the extortion charge involving his acceptance of approximately $ 127,000 in cash from a construction company and three counts of filing false tax returns for 1984-86, during which the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> says he underreported his income by $ 190,500. <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON>, who was a highway commissioner for 21 years, remains free on a $ 5,000 personal recognizance bond. He also posted a $ 205,000 bond to cover back taxes, interest and penalties. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> recommended <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON>, 67, be sentenced to two years on the extortion charge and placed on five years' probation on the income tax charges, as well as a $ 40,000 fine. <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON> must pay all back taxes plus interest and penalties. She said the extortion charge carries a maximum penalty of 20 years in jail and a $ 250,000 fine. Filing false income tax returns carries a three-year jail term and a $ 100,000 fine for each count. <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON> announced his Dec. 31 resignation in a Dec. 21 statement which said: `` I am resigning because I have made a mistake, and I must now pay the price for that mistake.'' On Wednesday, <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> sentenced a second highway commisioner, <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON>, 59, to a six-year prison term on a federal extortion charge. He also received a five-year suspended sentence and was ordered to pay a $ 100,000 fine on a tax evasion charge. The three members of the <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> are elected only from the district which they represent and act autonomously in matters concerning road construction and maintenance within their district. There has been considerable public discussion about changing the system to make the commission a statewide board, but so far the Legislature has taken no action to change the system. In the meantime, special elections have been held to replace <PERSON> Waggoner </PERSON> and <PERSON> Joiner </PERSON>.
