<FIRST>r i AM-China-Factory     02-09 0548</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-China-Factory,0569</SECOND>
<HEAD>Private Factory Forced to Go Public After Attacks, Lawsuit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN POMFRET</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The owner of a private factory was forced to give his business to the state after peasants, wanting part of his profits, attacked the plant and officials jealous of his success sued him, a newspaper said Thursday. The report in the official <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Youth </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> illuminated some of the problems faced by individual firms in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, which has been experimenting with private enterprise the last few years. Some businessmen have incurred the people's wrath because they fire people as they attempt to break the `` iron rice bowl,'' <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s tradition of lifetime employment Others have been attacked because local residents are jealous of their success. The story of <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Jianfa </PERSON> falls into the second category. In 1982, <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> scrimped and borrowed about $ 9,500 to open an ironworks factory in <LOCATION> Jiangyin </LOCATION>, a small city in the eastern province of <LOCATION> Jiangsu </LOCATION>. After two years, <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> had repaid his debts, `` set down some roots and even cleared a profit,'' the story said. `` But as the sound of the hammer brought profits, so it also brought troubles.'' First, a representative of local government called on him, saying he had to start sharing his profits because his factory was on public land. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> had already agreed to pay the electrical, water and electric plowing fees of 100 households. `` But this little problem was just a sign of things to come,'' the article said. One day a fisherman could n't catch anything in a river near the factory. `` He alleged the hammers of <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Jianfa </PERSON>'s factory had scared away his fish,'' the paper said. The man gathered about 60 of his friends and they attacked the factory, smashing its windows, cutting its power supply and blocking its docks. Production stopped. `` Even though <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> had thousands of dollars, he could n't get any help, because his factory was privately owned,'' the paper said. `` So <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Jianfa </PERSON> took one step back in order to go two steps forward and gave the factory to the state-run production team.'' In so doing, <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> united his interests with those of a collective. <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> signed a contract with the production team, `` changed from ` boss' to factory manager, and under the umbrella of a state-run business, looked forward to the future.'' Soon, government officials from <LOCATION> Wuxi </LOCATION>, a nearby city, came to the factory, `` saying they had received a tip. They wanted to see his books.'' It appeared another government agency also wanted a piece of <PERSON> Ren </PERSON>'s profits. `` This fellow gave his factory to the production team but did n't give it to us,'' the newspaper quoted officials in the other agency as saying `` We've got to send this guy to jail.'' Within days 100 people had signed on to sue <PERSON> Ren </PERSON>. `` But in court there was nothing but silence,'' the report said. `` What crimes did Ren commit? Nobody really knew.'' The only `` crime'' was that <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> had gotten rich. The suit was dropped but the marathon struggle over interests had kept the factory silent six months. In summing up, the story said <PERSON> Ren </PERSON> <PERSON> Jianfa </PERSON> was no Lei Feng, a <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military hero known for his selflessness. `` But,'' it said, `` he understands that if you want to succeed here you have to have dauntless strength.''
</TEXT>
