<HEAD>Troops Round Up 175 Palestinians in Hebron Soccer Stadium</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY SEDOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers rounded up about 175 Palestinians in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> on Thursday and forced them to sit blindfolded and bound for up to 16 hours in a soccer stadium, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> and Israeli witnesses said. Riots erupted outside the Megiddo Prison for a second straight day after <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports circulated that a second Palestinian had died of wounds sustained in a riot there Wednesday, <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio reported. Police said an Israeli settler killed when his car went up in flames in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> on Wednesday appeared to be the victim of a terror attack, but an investigation was continuing. `` It is reasonable it was terrorist,'' <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> police commander <PERSON> Haim </PERSON> <PERSON> Malcha </PERSON> said on <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio. `` Even though the results are preliminary, it seems unreasonable there was any other cause.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> radio said laboratory tests determined the car was not hit by a gasoline-filled bottle or firebomb because no glass fragments were found. But the tests uncovered a large quantity of flammable liquid in the driver's seat, the radio said. It said police suspected the car was either hit with a flaming plastic bottle or that gasoline was thrown at it. The settler, <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> <PERSON> Jerassi </PERSON>, 38, was the 16th Israeli to die since the Palestinian uprising in the occupied territories began Dec. 8, 1987. At least 379 Palestinians have died, most from Israeli gunfire. <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> reports said 17-year-old <PERSON> Nidal </PERSON> <PERSON> Zuhdi </PERSON> <PERSON> Deeb </PERSON> died after being shot by troops trying to quell Wednesday's disturbance at Megiddo Prison in northern <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. The army said it was checking the report. The radio said Thursday's riot was quickly subdued by prison guards and there were no casualties. In the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Strip </LOCATION>, troops shot and wounded nine Palestinians, including a 9-year-old girl and a 10-year-old boy from <LOCATION> Gaza </LOCATION>'s Mughazi refugee camp, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> doctors said. Both were struck in the head with rubber-coated steel bullets, they said. The army did not confirm any of the shootings. Troops with lists of suspects began rounding up Palestinians overnight in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bank </LOCATION> city of <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, detaining about 175 in a soccer stadium where they were forced to sit cross-legged on the ground until 2:30 p.m. Thursday, <PERSON> Arab </PERSON> witnesses and an <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> photographer said. Many were in their pajamas and had their hands tied behind their backs. Some were blindfolded. The Palestinians apparently were suspected of planning an action against <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> authorities in <LOCATION> Hebron </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Israeli </LOCATION> sources said. Arab witnesses said the detainees were given water but no food. One of the Palestinians was slapped twice by a soldier, they said. Dozens of the detainees were later moved from the soccer field, apparently to detention centers for questioning, the witnesses said. The rest were sent home. Also Thursday, the army sealed three Palestinian homes and demolished a fourth belonging to Palestinians accused of attacks on Israelis. One of the residences sealed belonged to <PERSON> Said </PERSON> <PERSON> Dadu </PERSON>, who allegedly threw explosives at the home of Trade and Industry Minister <PERSON> Ariel </PERSON> <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> in the Arab quarter of the walled <LOCATION> Old </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>.
