<HEAD>Hezbollah Pulls Out of Southern Lebanese Villages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JBAA, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Iranian-backed Moslem militiamen on Thursday pulled out of captured villages in the south under terms of a peace accord that ended their nine-month fight with Syrian-allied forces. The fundamentalist fighters of <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God, took refuge in hideouts in mountains near <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>'s security zone. But there was no immediate move by their <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> rivals, the Amal militia, to take over the villages of <LOCATION> Jbaa </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ein </PERSON> <PERSON> Bouswar </PERSON>. Some angry villagers said they want both militias to stay out. <PERSON> Ahmad </PERSON> <PERSON> Raad </PERSON>, a member of <LOCATION> Jbaa </LOCATION>'s municipal government, walked out of his bomb-scarred house and shouted: `` We do n't want militiamen any more: Neither Amal nor <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Fatima </PERSON> <PERSON> Qobeissie </PERSON>, a housewife, yelled: `` The militias have ruined our village! We do n't want them back! `` Three rockets hit our house, but luckily we were hiding in a bomb shelter,'' she said. `` Who's going to compensate us for our losses?'' The withdrawal was part of a peace treaty reached last month under supervision of <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. The pullout came 39 days after the radical <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> seized <LOCATION> Jbaa </LOCATION> and <PERSON> Ein </PERSON> <PERSON> Bouswar </PERSON> in an assault on <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> last month. Amal recaptured most of the mountainous region in a string of counter-offensives but failed to dislodge <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> from the mountaintop villages near <LOCATION> Sidon </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Mattout </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Jbaa </LOCATION> that his forces withdrew before dawn to bases on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Safi </LOCATION> near the western end of the security zone. <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> set up the buffer zone, which runs up to 10 miles deep into neighboring <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>, when it withdrew most of its occupation army from south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in 1985. <PERSON> Mattout </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> may maintain bases on <LOCATION> Mount </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Safi </LOCATION> under the <LOCATION> Damascus </LOCATION> agreement. <PERSON> Jamal </PERSON> <PERSON> Qalqas </PERSON>, an Amal representative, toured the two villages after <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> militiamen withdrew and called on civilians who evacuated the area during the fighting to return home. At least 173 people were killed in the fighting that broke out in south <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> Dec. 31 and spread to the Shiite-dominated south. It was the latest eruption in a power struggle for control of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 1 million Shiites, the country's biggest sect <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> advocates creating an Iranian-style Islamic republic in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The more secular and nationalist <ORGANIZATION> Amal </ORGANIZATION> favors a multisect government in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in which Moslems would hold an equal share of power with traditionally dominant Christians. In the <LOCATION> Chouf </LOCATION> mountains southeast of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> on Thursday, gunmen shot and killed a senior aide of <PERSON> Walid </PERSON> <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>, a Druse Moslem military leader, police said. <PERSON> Anwar </PERSON> <PERSON> Fatayeri </PERSON>, political bureau member of <PERSON> Jumblatt </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Progressive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Socialist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, was gunned down in an ambush on a road nine miles from <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>. No one claimed responsibility.
