<HEAD>Photos of Dead Dogs Ordered Removed From Dog Show</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Organizers of a world famous dog show ordered the <ORGANIZATION> Royal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> for the Prevention of Cruelty to Animals to remove photographs of dead dogs from an exhibit, calling them shocking and upsetting. One picture showed a pile of dogs killed by injections because their owners could not be found. Another was of a bulging garbage bag captioned, `` This doggy bag contains a dead doggy.'' The society used the photographs in full-page newspaper advertisements Sunday to launch a campaign for a dog registration plan to deter people from buying pet dogs and then abandoning them. It had included the photos in the society's exhibit at the Crufts Dog Show, the 103-year-old exhibition that began Thursday, hoping to enlist the support of dog lovers. The charity said that since government licenses for dogs were scrapped last year, it has had to slaughter 1,000 healthy dogs daily because their owners can not be traced. `` We do not like this horror-comic approach,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Sinnatt </PERSON>, secretary of the <ORGANIZATION> Kennel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION> that runs the Crufts show.
