<HEAD>Lawmakers Unveil Bill Aimed At Opening Permanent Waste Site</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BURNS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Rep. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Skeen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.M. </LOCATION>, unveiled a bill Thursday aimed at clearing the way for opening the nation's first permanent nuclear waste repository. The legislation, co-sponsored by Rep. <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Idaho </LOCATION>, was designed also to end a political impasse between the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> and the states of <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> that threatens to force the closing of a key nuclear weapons facility. The bill would give jurisdiction of more than 10,000 acres of federal lands in southern <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> to the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, which is seeking to gain safety clearance to open the Waste Isolation Pilot Plant. The waste dump had been scheduled to open last October, but technical problems and questions about the long-term integrity of the repository have delayed the opening. The delay prompted <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> Gov. <PERSON> Cecil </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> late last year to seal his state's borders against shipments of hazardous wastes from the Rocky Flats plutonium processing plant near <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION>. <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, in turn, said it would close the plant in May unless a new storage site is found for the contaminated materials that have been accumulating at Rocky Flats since <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> imposed his ban. Rocky Flats is the only plant capable of processing plutonium for nuclear weapons. <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> has said he would reconsider his ban on waste shipments to <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION> if certain conditions were met, including the introduction of legislation to speed the opening of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> repository. <PERSON> Stallings </PERSON> told a news conference it was not clear whether <PERSON> Andrus </PERSON> was ready to reconsider. Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.M. </LOCATION>, said he planned to introduce a bill later this month that would place stricter environmental conditions on opening the repository. <PERSON> Skeen </PERSON> said he and other congressmen with an interest in the waste issue would work with <PERSON> Richardson </PERSON> to draft a compromise bill to try to get the pilot plant open by the end of the year. A key point of dispute is how much waste material should be allowed into the site during an initial testing period. <PERSON> Skeen </PERSON> said the matter could not be resolved until the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> furnished more information about its plans for the five-year testing program.
