<FIRST>r w AM-TaxReturns     02-09 0668</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Tax Returns,660</SECOND>
<HEAD>Error Delays 450,000 Tax Refunds</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM LUTHER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Tax Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A human error in running a computer has delayed 450,000 federal tax refunds by a week, but the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday there is no comparison with the computer problems that made a disaster of the 1985 filing season. `` The situation was uncovered immediately and remedial steps were taken so that no taxpayers were inconvenienced,'' <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> said of the latest problem. `` People are going to get their refund checks in the four-to-six-week time frame that is typical at this time of the year,'' said <PERSON> Ellen </PERSON> <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> director of public affairs. But checks for those who filed in the second or third week of January will be mailed Feb. 17, rather than Feb. 10 as had been planned. Millions of tax refunds were delayed for several weeks in 1985 because of problems with a new $ 103 million computer system. <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> was asked whether taxpayers should be worried that the new problem might be the first warning of a recurrence. `` Absolutely not,'' he said. This year, he said, there was no problem with the computer itself or the instructions fed into it. `` The refund checks were in the correct amount, the bills that would have been generated were in the correct amount. `` We learned from the 1985 problems and we wanted to make sure that whatever was needed to be done was done ... that no taxpayer would receive an erroneous notice,'' <PERSON> Keith </PERSON> said. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> deliberately delayed mailing the 450,000 refund checks, as well as any tax-due notices arising from returns filed early this year, until the human error could be corrected. That error was made at the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> computing center in <LOCATION> Martinsburg </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> W. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Va. </LOCATION>, where all master files on individual taxpayers are kept and where refund checks are authorized The problem occurred because the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> late last year announced that taxpayers in six states _ <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Indiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mississippi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Alabama </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Minnesota </LOCATION> _ should file their returns to a different service center this year in order to even the workload among the 10 centers where returns are processed. <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> taxpayers, for example, used to file to <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>; now, they file to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. But those changes were not taken into account at the <LOCATION> Martinsburg </LOCATION> center. Thus, if a <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> taxpayer had a question about his or her account or refund, the computer would have generated a notice directing the taxpayer to correspond with the <LOCATION> Memphis </LOCATION> center, rather than <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>. To avoid such erroneous notices, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> simply delayed the checks. With the exception of that problem, Ms. <PERSON> Murphy </PERSON> said, the filing season is going well. Through Feb. 3, she said, 8.45 million returns had been filed _ down 7.6 percent from the same time last year _ and 2.75 million had been processed, an increase of almost 14 percent. The figures are in line with recent years, when _ for reasons that neither the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> nor outside experts can explain _ the number of taxpayers filing early in the season declined each year. Through Jan. 27, the <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> had certified 95,000 refunds totaling $ 72 million, an average of about $ 751 per check. The number of refunds was down 12.6 percent and the average refund was up 4.2 percent. The <ORGANIZATION> IRS </ORGANIZATION> expects 109 million returns this year and, as in most years, about 75 percent will qualify for refunds. A check of early returns shows many taxpayers who do not itemize deductions are failing to claim the standard deduction. The agency will correct that error, but any refund will be delayed. Another common error is a failure by a filer _ usually a young person with a part-time job _ to check a box indicating whether he or she can be claimed as a dependent by another. Also near the top of the mistake list are mathematics errors, failure of low-income working families to claim the earned-income credit, and failing to use taxable income to calculate taxes owed.
</TEXT>
