<HEAD>Consecration Of Female Bishop Won't End Controversy Over Women Of
the Cloth</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DIAMOND</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> is mustering full pomp and ceremony to install <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> as the first woman bishop in a 2,000-year <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> line dating to the apostles. The worldwide attention expected for Saturday's events goes far beyond anything the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> usually confronts and reflects a debate that has simmered within church ranks and now threatens to spill over into Christianity at large. Some 8,300 tickets have already been distributed for the consecration. Demand has forced church officials to move the ceremony from <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Paul </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cathedral </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> to the cavernous <ORGANIZATION> Hynes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Convention </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION>, which has room for spectators, a chorus of 130, television cameras and a large contingent of journalists. Though no one is announcing any last-minute effort to block the appointment, a good many of the attendees can be expected to hold their breath when the ritual requires presiding Bishop <PERSON> Edmund </PERSON> <PERSON> Browning </PERSON> to intone: `` If any of you know any reason why we should not proceed, let it now be made known.'' The 58-year-old former head of a left-wing religious publishing company has been a subject of some controversy within the church since Sept. 24, when the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Diocese </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> elected her suffragan, or assistant bishop. Women have been priests in the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> since 1976. But becoming an bishop is a question of much higher magnitude. <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> would become the first woman to reach that height in any of the three major branches of Christianity _ Roman Catholicism, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodoxy </ORGANIZATION> and Anglicanism _ that trace bishops in a direct line back to the Apostles of <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON>. After the election last September, debate quickly ensued across the country among 118 church committees responsible for confirming the election. A traditionalist faction of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, led by the <ORGANIZATION> Evangelical </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, rallied in opposition to <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' elevation. Now, prelates and observers on both sides of the issue are concerned that the stakes may be even larger than the unity of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, which is a branch of worldwide Anglicanism. The Roman Catholic, Eastern Orthodox and Anglican churches have been involved for more than a decade in discussions over easing their centuries-old differences. `` And they have made great progress,'' said <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Solheim </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Boston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> diocese. `` For Roman Catholics, the idea of a woman standing at the altar representing Christ is totally unacceptable.'' Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> in December issued what Solheim called `` ominous noises'' about the impending consecration of <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>. The pope warned of `` painful and deplorable consequences'' of the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> going forward with the consecration of a female bishop. `` The constant line of tradition, common to all the churches, can not be so easily interupted,'' he said. `` This has great ecumenical consequences,'' said Bishop <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Davies </PERSON> of the Evangelical and <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mission </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Austin </LOCATION>. A female bishop might be acceptable if all of Christianity approved in an official way, he said. `` But we're a small church. In taking the leadership in this, we just denigrate the progress we've made in having communion throughout the world. <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Clementine </PERSON> <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> this week was the calm at the center of the storm, recovering from a head cold on a church retreat. She could not be reached for comment because she has no access to a telephone at the retreat, <ORGANIZATION> Solheim </ORGANIZATION> said. Some of the opposition to her elevation stemmed from her decidedly leftist political views which she conveyed in the publication, The Witness, issued by the <ORGANIZATION> Episcopal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Publishing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, where she has been an Episcopal priest since 1980. The periodical has published articles supporting homosexual rights and the Nicaraguan Sandinista government and criticizing the church for failing to fully bring women into church leadership. The Rev. <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Politzer </PERSON>, president of the traditionalist <ORGANIZATION> Prayer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Book </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, described <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> as `` pro-Marxist. Her writings are snide and sarcastic. She is unfit to be a bishop.'' Some also have questioned <PERSON> Harris </PERSON>' qualifications because of her lack of a college degree and full seminary training. A black woman and a veteran of the civil rights marches of the 1960s, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> has been outspoken for civil rights and feminism and she is unapologetic about her views. But at a recent news conference in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Harris </PERSON> sought to ease concerns by saying her work for the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> diocese would focus on sacramental and pastoral duties rather than involvement in political affairs.
