<HEAD>UNITA Envoy Seeking More U.S. Weapons, Raises Doubts About Cuban
Pullout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RUTH SINAI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An envoy for the rebels fighting the Angolan government said Thursday he is seeking additional <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> anti-aircraft and anti-tank missiles to combat a predicted offensive by Cuban-backed troops. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> da </PERSON> <PERSON> Costa </PERSON> <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON>, who holds the rank of brigadier general in the Union for the Total Independence of <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION>, also urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to improve the monitoring of Cuban troop pullout from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> against any attempts by <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> to cheat. <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said at a news conference that he was `` satisfied with the meetings'' he has had with <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> officials about his organization's requests. But he also criticized parts of the U.S.-sponsored agreement signed last December that calls for the pullout of all Cuban troops from <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> and grants independence to neighboring <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION> from South African rule. `` There are flaws in the agreement that are not of our liking,'' he said. <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> urged the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to use `` sophisticated means'' to monitor the troop withdrawal, claiming that <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> had sent in fresh troops to replace some of the 3,000 who were pulled out under the agreement last month. He said there were no accurate figures for <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops, who have been helping the Marxist Angolan government since it gained independence from <LOCATION> Portugal </LOCATION> in 1975. Troop estimates from a variety of sources have ranged from between 50,000 and 60,000. Under the agreement, <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> has promised to provide accurate figures by April 1, once the 90-member <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> observer group is in place. The commander of the force, Brazilian Gen. <PERSON> Pericles </PERSON> <PERSON> Ferreira </PERSON> <PERSON> Gomes </PERSON>, says his 10-nation group will rely on Angolan and Cuban figures during the withdrawal. But <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said that could lead to cheating. He said the 27-month pullout timetable means <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> troops will remain in <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> one year after Namibian independence, giving <LOCATION> Cuba </LOCATION> a chance to send some of the troops to its ally <LOCATION> Namibia </LOCATION>. Based on troop movements and weapon stockpiling, <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> predicted that Cuban-backed Angolan troops would launch two or three offensives against <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> in southern <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> between May and July, before the Aug. 1 deadline for the Cubans to move northward of the 15th parallel. He said <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> needs long-range artillery pieces, anti-aircraft and anti-tank missiles. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> already provides <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> with shoulder-fired Stinger anti-aircraft missiles and TOW anti-tank missiles as part of a covert aid package estimated at $ 15 million annually. <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> needs more arms because the Soviets recently delivered to <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> 12 Cuban-flown MiG-25 fighter jets and some Mi-35 helicopter gunships. A <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> official, speaking on condition of anonymity, says <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> met with several people in the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> but she declined to elaborate. `` We provide appropriate and adequate assistance to <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>,'' she said, but said policy bans discussion of covert aid. Much of <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION>'s arsenal, which is mostly of Soviet origin, was brought in through <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> African-controlled </LOCATION> territory. But this has stopped under terms of the tripartite agreement, along with the $ 80 million South African annual aid package, he said. In a separate interview, <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> had `` increased the capability of all airfields'' to accommodate long-range aircraft, indicating that these bases would be used to resupply the organization now that its land lines have been blocked. He also said <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> has a two-to-three year stock of military equipment it received through <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> and from three African countries which he declined to name. Despite reports to the contrary, <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> enjoys `` moral and diplomatic support'' from about 15 other African states, he added. At the news conference, <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said he had asked the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> to send a signal to several African nations, such as <LOCATION> Senegal </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Kenya </LOCATION>, of support for a dialogue between <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> and the Angolan government. Such a signal would spur these governments to put pressure on <LOCATION> Angola </LOCATION> to negotiate a cease-fire and power-sharing agreement with the rebels, he said. <ORGANIZATION> UNITA </ORGANIZATION> will not accept a government offer for clemency because `` we are not criminals,'' <PERSON> Fernandes </PERSON> said, preferring to increase its military struggle to place additional pressure on the government to negotiate.
