<HEAD>With AM-Bush Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Score Bush Child Care Plan</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DENISE CABRERA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Child care experts Thursday criticized President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposed $ 1,000 child care tax credit as being too low and insufficient to address the range of problems faced by most parents. `` It's really irrelevant to the child care needs of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Zigler </PERSON>, director of the <ORGANIZATION> Bush </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> in Child Development and Social Policy at <ORGANIZATION> Yale </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Zigler </PERSON>, speaking as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> opened a series of hearings on child care, called the proposal `` a non-solution.'' `` And the amount of money is too low. In an era where child care costs $ 3,000 and $ 4,000 a year, $ 1,000 does n't do much for that,'' said <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Norton </PERSON> <PERSON> Grubb </PERSON>, a professor of education at the <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> at <LOCATION> Berkeley </LOCATION>. The committee estimates full-time child care costs at an average $ 3,000 annually per child. That means a family with two children, in which both parents work at minimum wage, spends more than half its income for child care. <PERSON> Zigler </PERSON>, a strong proponent of school-based day-care, said the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal does n't address the obstacles faced by single-working mothers or move to eliminate the `` two-tier'' care system he said is developing between low-income families and others who can afford private care. <PERSON> Grubb </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s failure to include a system of regulation in the proposal would result in poor families spending the money for other needs. `` The money in that proposal is not restricted to child care. Most of the funds in that proposal, if enacted, would not go for child care. They would go for food, housing, utilities, clothing and other necessities like that,'' said <PERSON> Grubb </PERSON>. <PERSON> Deborah </PERSON> <PERSON> Phillips </PERSON>, a <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Virginia </ORGANIZATION> professor of psychology, told the panel the proposal does n't address the quality of day care. She said quality should not be sacrificed because government policy frames it `` as a luxury issue in child care.'' Meanwhile, Sen. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, ranking Republican on the <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, said he will introduce a bill to expand existing child care tax credits for families with incomes under $ 25,000 and assist states in improving current programs. <PERSON> Packwood </PERSON>'s proposal would provide a maximum tax credit of $ 960 for one child and $ 1,920 for two or more children. The credit would be fully refundable and could be made available through payroll withholdings. Current law provides for tax savings of $ 720 for one child and $ 1,440 for two or more children and it is not refundable.
