<HEAD>See More Oranges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The nation's orange harvest for the 1988-89 season is estimated at about 215 million boxes, virtually unchanged from the previous forecast a month ago but 7 percent more than last season, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. The <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> crop, based on Feb. 1 indications, was estimated at 150 million boxes, unchanged from last month but 9 percent more than in 1987-88. <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> production was forecast at 61 million boxes, the same as in January but 4 percent more than a year ago. The <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION> crop was forecast at 2 million boxes, unchanged from January and up 10 percent from last season. The <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> harvest, at 1.85 million boxes, was indicated at 6 percent more than the January forecast and up 29 percent from 1987-88.
