<HEAD>Buy More Grain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought another 600,000 metric tons of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> wheat at subsidized prices, the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> said Thursday. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldthwait </PERSON>, acting general sales manager for the department's <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agricultural </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION>, said the wheat was part of an authorization of more than 2 million tons under the Export Enhancement Program, or EEP. <PERSON> Goldthwait </PERSON> said the wheat is for shipment in March. Counting some left over from a previous <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangement and 2 million tons authorized Jan. 25, the Soviets have more than 1.4 million tons still available under the program. With the latest sale, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has bought about 2.6 million tons of wheat for delivery in the sixth year of a long-term supply agreement, which was extended last fall to run through Dec. 31, 1990. A metric tons is about 2,205 pounds and is equal to 36.7 bushels of wheat. The 600,000 tons are equal to about 22 million bushels worth around $ 90 million at recent <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> farm prices. The <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangement lets private exporters sell wheat and other designated commodities to specified countries at reduced prices in order to meet foreign competition. The exporters then collect free government surpluses of grain or other products as bonuses, or subsidies. Sales for delivery in the sixth year of the agreement also included about 10.2 million tons of corn, along with 450,000 tons of soybeans, 1.4 million tons of soybean meal, and 508,900 tons of grain sorghum. <PERSON> Goldthwait </PERSON> said the 600,000 tons of wheat were sold by <ORGANIZATION> Ferruzzi </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> USA </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 100,000 tons; <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Grain </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> a, 250,000; <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Dreyfus </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, 200,000; and <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> States </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, 50,000 The companies will get subsidy of $ 23.01 per ton, or about 63 cents per bushel under the <ORGANIZATION> EEP </ORGANIZATION> arrangement.
