hem,'' she said. Many people go to church only once a year or not at all, she said, and do n't feel comfortable in the presence of clergy. `` You're sick You're not at your best. Maybe you're here for something very personal,'' Ms. <PERSON> Lipp </PERSON> said. `` They do n't want to see some strange minister.'' But to assuage the clergy, the hospital agreed to emphasize the question during admissions and have patients sign a card accepting or rejecting religious visitors. Ministers at other hospitals, however, see the move as a bad trend. `` This sounds to me like an anti-religious move,'' said the Rev. <PERSON> Charles </PERSON> <PERSON> Clements </PERSON> of the Roman Catholic Archdiocese of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>. `` It certainly causes complications in ministering to the sick if you ca n't find them.''
