<FIRST>r w AM-FordHazard     02-09 0474</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Ford Hazard,450</SECOND>
<HEAD>Safety Group Says 5 Million Ford-made Cars Pose Hazard</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID BRISCOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Badly designed fuel filler pipes on 5 million <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> cars pose a fire danger that already has caused more than 200 deaths, a lawyer-founded group said Thursday. A <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the company is not aware of any hazardous condition that would warrant a recall of older models. Officials of the <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Injury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reduction </ORGANIZATION> told a news conference they want the company to spend $ 250 million to recall and fix the fuel tank assemblies on the cars, a variety of models made since 1965. Institute president <PERSON> Benjamin </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelly </PERSON> said the hazardous design has been the subject of several suits around the country, most ending in settlements. <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jerald </PERSON> <PERSON> terHorst </PERSON> said requiring automakers to modify older models to include each improvement in the product would mean that `` innovations and improvements would soon come to a halt.'' He said the company has confidence in the safety of its cars' fuel systems <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Perry </PERSON>, an insitute member from <LOCATION> Corpus </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Christi </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION>, said if <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> fails to act, the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> or <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> should step in to force a recall. <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said he has been involved in nine cases involving fires in Ford-made cars, all ending in settlement. He said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has never acknowledged liability and has settled on the condition that amounts it paid not be disclosed. He said <ORGANIZATION> Ford </ORGANIZATION> has acknowledged in court documents that 221 people have died in crashes involving fuel tank fires in Ford-made cars since 1965 and the institute believes from 50 to 100 more deaths have occurred with about 3,000 people injured. The defect, he said, is caused by a design that has the fuel tank filler pipe rigidly attached to the vehicles' fender, causing the hose to be pulled out in a rear-end collision. This causes gas and highly combustible vapors to escape and be easily ignited by sparks and heat generated in a crash, <PERSON> Perry </PERSON> said. He said the danger can be avoided by lengthening the pipe, attaching it to the fuel tank and providing a `` breakaway'' device so it will detach from the outside panel, at a cost of about $ 50 per car. The institute said the systems was installed in full-size Fords, Mercurys and Lincolns built from 1965 to 1985; in some full-size 1986 Fords and Mercurys; in 1974-79 Lincoln Mark IV and Mark V models, and in some Thunderbirds, <ORGANIZATION> Cougars </ORGANIZATION>, Pintos, <ORGANIZATION> Bobcats </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Mustangs </ORGANIZATION>, Capris, Fairmonts, <ORGANIZATION> Zephyrs </ORGANIZATION> and <PERSON> Granadas </PERSON> built from 1970 to 1981. The institute, which describes itself as a non-profit research and educational organization concerned with reducing injuries resulting from product defects, estimated that 20 million cars were built with the fuel tank design and that 5 million of them are still on the road.
