<HEAD>Miners End Strike; Walesa Asks Workers to Give Talks a Chance</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS throughout to UPDATE with Walsa in Krakow</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DEBORAH G. SEWARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KRAKOW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity founder <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> interceded to end a strike at <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s largest power complex Thursday and asked restive workers to give his negotiations with the government a chance. At a rally in a Roman Catholic church for employees of the huge Nova Huta steel mill, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> spent more than an hour explaining the talks with communist authorities through which Solidarity hopes to become legal again. He urged workers to put aside local grievances long enough for the negotiations, which began Monday in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, to bear fruit. Strikes crippled the Nova Huta mill last spring and summer. A strike of coal miners at the Belchatow power complex 90 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, which supplies one-fifth of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s electricity, was ended with the help of a mediator sent by <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, but other labor tension continued The <ORGANIZATION> Solidarity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Information </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Service </ORGANIZATION> said workers in the <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION> coke department were refusing overtime, and the official news agency <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said the same was true of ambulance staffs in <LOCATION> Poznan </LOCATION> province, western <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> PAP </ORGANIZATION> said about 460 workers at a machine plant near <LOCATION> Czestochowa </LOCATION> started a strike Thursday for higher pay, cuts in administrative staff and better working conditions. Government delegates and representatives of the opposition met for seven hours Thursday in a working group on trade union issues and expressed optimism that technical details for restoring Solidarity's legal status could be worked out. Among major questions remaining are whether a `` social contract'' can be made on economic and political reforms, and the form of new parliamentary elections. Authorities have made agreement on those topics, being negotiated by other working groups, a condition for legalizing the union. <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON>, national spokesman for Solidarity, told reporters the union wants a separate law making it legal again and expressed satisfaction with the prospects. `` It's not formal approval'' so far, `` but it's optimistic because the authorities asked for technical details,'' he said. `` So they treat -LRB- our position -RRB- as a serious thing and will consider it as such.'' <PERSON> Alexander </PERSON> <PERSON> Kwasniewski </PERSON>, a government minister who took part in the meeting, said the discussion now revolves around how the legalization would occur. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> founded Solidarity in <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>, where he still works as a shipyard electrician, during the labor turmoil of 1980 and the government initially accepted it as the first independent trade union in the Soviet bloc. It was suppressed after the declaration of martial law in December 1981, however, and later outlawed. After attending the first part of Thursday's negotiations in <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> left for the evening Mass and rally in <LOCATION> Nowa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Huta </LOCATION>, on the outskirts of <LOCATION> Krakow </LOCATION> in southern <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. He is making a two-day tour of the southern region to reassure skeptical workers about the negotiations with the government. Speaking to a crowd of about 3,000 people after Mass in the Mistrzejowice church, which was lined with Solidarity banners, he declared: `` I do n't believe in the government, but there is a possiblity for pluralism. As <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> I must do everything, or take every opportunity peacefully, to build a better <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>.'' The union leader, who won the 1983 Nobel Peace Prize, has apologized to audiences lately for `` too elegant'' by wearing a suit and tie to the negotiations. He appeared at the rally in a sportcoat and jeans. When members of the audience shouted out grievances against the steel mill management and behavior of local authorities, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> appeared impatient. `` Each one of us has grievances and reasons to strike, and we have to get out of this,'' he said. `` If there is a chance at the round table, we have to take it.'' Solidarity can address specific problems when it is allowed to function legally, he said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s initial appeal, in an interview with state radio, was broadcast as the working group on unions began its meeting. He called the Belchatow strike `` another proof that we should reach agreement on the most important things as soon as possible and restore the organization called Solidarity.'' Wildcat strikes could be avoided if an organized union spoke for the workers, he said, and told Solidarity's supporters: `` <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> is appealing for a chance for the round table. We have been waiting for so many years, we can wait a few days more.'' The unprecedented talks, first proposed during severe labor unrest in August and expected to last up to six weeks, are intended to create a national consensus for solving <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s severe economic, social and political problems.
