 Police said they arrested two of deposed President <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s government ministers Thursday and caught the former central bank president trying to flee with a large amount of cash. No charges were specified, but the detentions appeared to be connected with alleged financial irregularities under Gen. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>, who ruled for nearly 35 years and was overthrown last week. <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> is in exile in <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON> <PERSON> Romeo </PERSON> <PERSON> Acosta </PERSON>, 75-year-old former head of the central bank, was arrested while trying cross the border to <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and confined to a police hospital, the authorities reported. They said said he was carrying $ 20,000, many traveler's checks and 12,000 West German marks. Police also reported the detentions of <PERSON> Adan </PERSON> <PERSON> Godoy </PERSON> <PERSON> Gimenez </PERSON>, former minister of public health, and <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Ortiz </PERSON> <PERSON> Ramirez </PERSON>, who was <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON>'s education minister. Officials in the provisional government of Gen. <PERSON> Andres </PERSON> <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, a longtime associate of <PERSON> Stroessner </PERSON> who ousted him Feb. 3, have been saying all week that officials of the former regime apparently enriched themselves with public funds. Central bank officials said Wednesday they would examine checks written by some `` government officials who are no longer government officials.'' With the dictator gone, exiles are returning from neighboring <LOCATION> Brazil </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Argentina </LOCATION> and such opposition politicians as <PERSON> Domingo </PERSON> <PERSON> Laino </PERSON> are interviewed on television. <PERSON> Rodriguez </PERSON>, who has called elections for May 1, is receiving dissident factions of the ruling <ORGANIZATION> Colorado </ORGANIZATI