<HEAD>Bush, in First Major Speech to Congress, Touts `Common Sense' Budget</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Updates, in top 10 grafs with more detail, reaction, picking
up in 6th graf pvs, ``It is</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in his maiden policy initiative to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, on Thursday proposed a $ 1.16 trillion `` common sense'' budget for fiscal 1990 that calls for less military but greater domestic spending than sought by President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The plan, which features a one-year freeze on scores of federal programs, calls for roughly $ 5 billion more spending than the budget submitted by former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> last month and carries out <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s oft-stated opposition to new taxes. `` Higher taxes ... are not the solution to the deficit problem,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s 193-page budget outline declares. But, while the measure supports many of the campaign vows made by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> in his 1988 presidential campaign _ more help for the homeless, for education, for child care and for cleaning up the environment _ it also leaves much of the federal budget up to negotiation with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Initial reaction from lawmakers was cordial. `` The Democratic <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> wants to work with this president in every way that we can,'' House Speaker <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> said in a taped response for the television networks. `` We'll give him our sincere cooperation. That does not mean obedience. It does mean our honest help and our very best advice.'' White House spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> was `` happy with the budget and eager to get on with the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> initiatives.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s first presidential speech, televised nationally at 9 p.m. EST, was expected to mix campaign promises with expressions of budget restraint and new overtures toward bipartisanship. But his budget was vague on exactly where all the money would come from to pay for initiatives. `` It is not as much as he promised but it is a start,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget director, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> G. </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, told a <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> briefing The budget director said that there was room for even more savings in federal spending if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> decided to go along with the dozens of programs that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> sought to terminate _ actions that for the most part the new <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget does not embrace. The new budget did not detail which programs should be cut beyond the general proposal for a spending freeze. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is ready to negotiate with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on a final budget `` all day and all night if that's what it takes,'' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> said. His budget, described as a `` common-sense approach to budgeting,'' calls for a one-year freeze on defense spending at the levels of inflation. And, it projects a federal deficit in the fiscal year that begins next Oct. 1 of $ 94.8 billion _ well within the $ 100 billion limit set by the Gramm-Rudman budget-balancing law. If the sale of government assets are included, the deficit would be even lower _ $ 91.1 billon. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget amendments call for an overall budget surplus of $ 3.8 billion by 1993. The plan seeks to put in motion a variety of campaign promises, including a proposed $ 1,000-per child tax credit for low-income families, a $ 3,000 tax deduction to help cover the costs of adoptions, an expansion of the Head Start program and a new plan to give grants to the nation's best high schools. It would also provide nearly $ 1 billion more in the upcoming year to fight `` the scourge of drugs'' and would restore some $ 1.7 billion in cuts sought by <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> in the Medicaid program for medical assistance for poor people. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal would also reduce to 15 percent from the current level of 28 percent to 33 percent the tax on most capital gains _ the profits from the sale of real estate, stocks or other assets. This proposal had drawn opposition in advance from congressional Democrats, who vowed to fight it as a tax benefiting mostly the rich. And there are other strains in <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s efforts to extend an `` offered hand'' to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. His speech comes as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is engaged in a protracted and divisive confirmation struggle over <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s nomination of former Sen. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Tower </PERSON> as defense secretary. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has said he stands firmly behind his nominee, despite recurring allegations of womanizing and excessive drinking that continue to stall the confirmation process. The budget plan presented few surprises. Most of its elements had been reported in the past. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> repeated <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s long-sought appeal for a constitutional amendment to balance the budget and authority to veto individual lines in spending bills. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who promised a `` kinder but gentler nation'' in his campaign, also proposed an overall increase of 70 percent in federal spending on `` the tragedy of men, women, and children living without homes.'' Much of the revenues needed to fund <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s new initiatives would come from spending freezes on a host of federal programs _ including all government military and civilian retirement benefits. However, Social Security benefits would not be affected under the plan. The president claims his capital gains proposal would generate $ 4 billion or so in revenue by stimulating new business investment, but many economists have disputed this and the proposal has already encountered stiff Demcoratic opposition. In fact, Rep. <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Rostenkowski </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ill </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ways </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Means </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, on Thursday promised all-out opposition to <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s proposal to reduce the capital gains tax Even so, Democratic leaders generally seemed ready to give <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the benefit of the doubt in his first speech to a joint session of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. `` I do n't think there's any particular effort on the part of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> to do anything expect to applaud what the president is about to say and to continue the kind of spirit that the president has been working very hard on ... in trying to develop a relationship with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>,'' said Rep. <PERSON> Dante </PERSON> <PERSON> Fascell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Fla </LOCATION>., Under regular procedures, the president's budget gets modified by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> into a final budget resolution, which then serves as an overall guide for legislation produced later by the appropriations and tax-writing committees <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s plan modifies a $ 1.15 trillion budget <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> submitted shortly before leaving office. The <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> plan called for a 2 percent increase in defense spending over inflation, proposed scores of cuts in domestic programs and projected a federal deficit of $ 92.5 billion.
