<HEAD>Bush's First Budget: Collision Between Campaign Rhetoric and Reality</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: UPDATES top 21 grafs with material from budget briefing; PICKS
UP 19th graf pvs bgng, `During the'</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Economics Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A new president's first budget is always a collision between campaign rhetoric and reality, and the budget <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> put forward Thursday could spell a quick end to his honeymoon with <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> the campaigner wanted to be the education president, stop the drug scourge, house the homeless and clean up the environment. And he promised that all the good things he wanted for the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> people could be accomplished without raising taxes. The critics charged that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would fail. Either the promises would go unfulfilled or the president would end up increasing taxes. But in a melody with a familiar refrain, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> came up up with a way out of his quandary. He said he will raise more revenue by cutting taxes. Strains of `` That Old Black Magic'' by <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. The tax <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has in mind is the capital gains levy, which taxes the profits earned from the sale of assets, such as stocks. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget projects a $ 5 billion increase in revenues for the 1990 fiscal year, which begins next Oct. 1, through enactment of the cut in the capital gains tax. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s capital gains tax helps the new president achieve a projected 1990 deficit of $ 91.1 billion, slightly bettering the $ 92.5 billion deficit <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> put forward one month ago in his final spending blueprint. That is accomplished through the $ 5 billion projected revenue gain from the cut in the capital gains tax and $ 2.6 billion in reductions <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposed making in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s 1990 military spending request. Currently the profits on sales of assets are counted just like other income, which means for high-income people a top tax rate of either 28 percent or 33 percent. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wants to cut the capital gains rate in 1990 to 15 percent for assets held one year or longer and projects the change would increase revenues by $ 5 billion as people sold assets to take advantage of the lower rate. But that revenue estimate comes with a big catch, many economists believe. It will lower government revenues for other years. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON>, an economist with <ORGANIZATION> Data </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, a <LOCATION> Lexington </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mass. </LOCATION>, economic consulting firm, said that much of the revenue would be lost in the current year, thus ballooning the size of the 1989 deficit, which is already projected to soar to $ 161 billion. `` I guarantee that you would lose about the same amount of revenue in 1989 that you will gain in 1990,'' <PERSON> Wyss </PERSON> said. `` If you know that the capital gains rate is going down on Jan. 1, you wo n't be selling a lot of stock at a profit in June. Democrats on Capitol Hill have another complaint. They say the capital gains tax cut, which was one of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s campaign promises, is nothing but the old <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> `` trickle down'' theory to benefit the rich. They contend that 85 percent of all capital gains are earned by the wealthiest 5 percent of Americans. They aimed their fire at the proposal in barbed remarks stripped of the bipartisan good feeling which surrounded <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s inaugural address. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Budget </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Sasser </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Tenn </LOCATION>., said that at a time of huge budget deficits it was `` simply unacceptable to be considering tax breaks for the very wealthiest segment of the American population. The capital gains tax was n't the only target drawing fire. Critics complained that in many other areas the amount of money <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is proposing to spend is minuscule when compared with the magnitude of the problem. Even before <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s joint address, his aides were busy lowering expectations, contending that in a time of tight budgets it was tough to fund new initiatives. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget director, <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>, told reporters at a briefing on the budget that the president had at least made a start toward fulfulling his pledge for a `` kinder, gentler'' nation. `` Is it as kind and gentle as everyone would like to be immediately, I think probably not. But we ca n't do absolutely everything at once,'' <PERSON> Darman </PERSON> told reporters. `` We will not be claiming to have solved all problems.'' During the campaign, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the deficit problem would simply melt by 1993 or 1994 if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> would enact his `` flexible freeze,'' whereby the overall rise in government spending is held to the increase in inflation each year. Some programs could climb faster than the inflation rate but only if other areas were pruned back. But the pruning is likely to be as difficult for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as it was for <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, said Thursday he was upset that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> had decided to leave in his budget a proposal also in <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s final budget to curb <ORGANIZATION> Medicare </ORGANIZATION> spending by $ 5 billion next year by trimming payments to doctors and hospitals. Such a cut, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said, `` leads to very serious problems because you have a lot of hospitals losing money on Medicare now and a lot of hospitals closing, particularly rural hospitals.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITORS: Martin Crutsinger has covered economics for The</NOTE>
