<BYLINE>By GUY B. DARST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Supplies are so short in Veterans Administration hospitals that nurses are scrounging thee little souvenir bars of soap and shampoo bottles from hotels to bring to <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> patients, a nurse told <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday. Supply accounts are frequently raided to pay salaries and avoid layoffs, an outside medical administrator told the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. <PERSON> Claudette </PERSON> <PERSON> Morissey </PERSON>, a nurse at the <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, veterans hospital and prsident of the <ORGANIZATION> Nurses </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, said in testimony submitted to the hearing, `` At one VA hospital in the south, nurses were frustrated by the refusal of -LRB- the -RRB- prosthetics -LRB- department -RRB- to supply wheel chair cushions for patients on the long term care unit. `` The nurses obtained a $ 25 donation, went to the local upholstery store and purchased a large foam mattress, and with an electric knife borrowed from the mother of one of the nurses, cut the foam to make wheel chair cushions for their patients.'' She did not identify the hospital, nor the hospital in other anecdotes: `` Nurses in one hospital brought in souvenir hotel soaps and shampoos for the patients, and in another, brought and cut large bars of soap in small pieces for patients to use.'' At her own hospital, she said, `` We can not properly monitor diabetic patients when there are no lancets to do finger sticks, no Chem Sticks for blood samples and no insulin syringes to use to give insulin if it is needed. This is the situation I have faced over the past month at my facility and I thank God there has been no crisis because of it.'' <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> spokesman, said he could not address allegations made at specific facilities in the VA system of 172 hospitals and more than 220 out-patient clinics. `` Where we have specific allegations, we would defer to the local hospital for comment,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` I would n't want to speak to the allegations of one nurse or one who represents a group of nurses as something that exists throughout the system.'' He said, however, that <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> director-designate <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> told the committee earlier this week that he would seek more money as a supplemental budget for 1989 and in the 1990 budget. `` He is aware of problems caused by the budget crunch,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. `` He met with President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> yesterday -LRB- Wednesday -RRB- and I am sure the problems of the hospitals were discussed.'' A Soviet report last week of hospital patients getting AIDS from unsterilized needles `` is a startling reminded to us in this country that mistakes can happen when the system starts to cut corners and workers perform daily under inordinate pressure as we do in the VA,'' she said. At congressional hearings last September, <LOCATION> VA </LOCATION> officials said they faced a $ 600 million to $ 1 billion shortfall in their $ 10.54 billion budget for medical care in the current fiscal year. <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON>, who will become secretary of veterans affairs when the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> becomes a cabinet department next month, said Tuesday he had met with Budget Director <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Darman </PERSON>. Declining to say if he thought a supplemental appropriation is needed for the current fiscal year, <PERSON> Derwinski </PERSON> said the meeting with <PERSON> Darman </PERS