<HEAD>Bush Calls for $2 Billion Cuts in Farm Programs</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MIKE ROBINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> called on lawmakers Thursday night to `` reform'' farm payment programs by reducing them by $ 2 billion next fiscal year, and the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> chairmen of both agriculture committees quickly said he was cutting too hard. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s overall fiscal blueprint for <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> programs appeared similar to what an outgoing President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> proposed a month ago, but some lawmakers expressed puzzlement over the fine print. Rep. <PERSON> Virginia </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, R-Neb., said the spending assumptions on which <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> based his outline were at sharp odds with <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>'s and that `` we will have much negotiating to do with the administration. She said farmers facing more drought could not take deeper cuts. `` Ultimately, Mother Nature and the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> will have the last word,'' the <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> lawmaker said. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> also had proposed $ 2 billion in cuts in payments by the government-owned <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> next year. But he sought to soften the blow for farmers by making $ 900 million of those payments this fiscal year. The <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Credit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> provides income-support payments to cotton, rice, wheat and feed grains producers as well as price-support loans that guard farmers against market slumps by making the government the buyer of last resort. Farm payments ballooned to more than $ 26 billion in 1986 but currently are costing taxpayers less than half of that as the farm economy continues to rebound from its doldrums of the early and mid-1980s. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget book said that `` provisions of current law were designed during the height of the farm crisis.'' `` It is now time to reform our farm programs and not wait until the current farm bill expires nearly two years hence,'' it said. It added that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has called on Agriculture Secretary <PERSON> Clayton </PERSON> <PERSON> K. </PERSON> <PERSON> Yeutter </PERSON> to `` work with the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to develop a specific set of initiatives designed to reduce federal farm expenditures by $ 2 billion in 1990.'' It reviewed an array of possible means of cutting the expenditures, ranging from a speeded up lowering of target prices used to calculate income-support payments to reducing the number of acres eligible for payments. On <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>, Rep. E. -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Kika </ORGANIZATION> -RRB- de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, issued a statement, saying he would `` make every effort possible to work harmoniously with my fellow Texan, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>.'' `` However, as it is currently proposed, the administration's 1990 budget still makes unreasonable demands upon agriculture which has already given $ 30 billion in cuts from proposed budgets over the last eight years.'' `` We in agriculture are prepared to make a fair contribution, but this administration is asking us to take cuts which represent considerably more than our fair share of the budget-balancing burden,'' de la <PERSON> Garza </PERSON> said. `` I would remind everyone that if we cut out the entire amount proposed for agricultural spending, it would still make only an almost infinitesimal impact on the total budget situation,'' he added. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON>, D-Vt., said the farm cuts envisioned would be double the automatic cuts prescribed if <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> failed to reduce the deficit under the Gramm-Rudman Act `` An agricultural budget cutting twice as deep as the Gramm-Rudman sequester is not a kinder and gentler budget,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said. `` When the 1990 reagan budget was released, I expressed my hope that it was designed to make the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget kinder and gentler,'' <PERSON> Leahy </PERSON> said. `` I also expressed my fear that the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> farm cuts would undermine a tough <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> negotiating position in the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> talks,'' he said. `` I am very disappointed that the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> budget is neither kinder to the farmer nor tougher on our competitors in the <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> negotiations.'' The <ORGANIZATION> GATT </ORGANIZATION> is the 97-nation General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade, which governs much of global commerce. Talks on updating the agreement have been going on for the last two years.
