<HEAD>Yacht Vying to Break 135-Year-Old Record Sails Toward Brewing Storm</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with 7 grafs to UPDATE sloop slowed by poor winds; probably
won't reach San Francisco until Saturday. Picks up 9th graf pvs: `Black
said...' A version also moved on sports wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JACK SCHREIBMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The yacht Thursday's Child has been slowed by poor winds in its quest to break a <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-to-San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Francisco </LOCATION> speed record that has stood for 135 years, the sloop's ground support said Thursday. `` It would be miraculous if they made it by Friday,'' said spokeswoman <PERSON> Nancy </PERSON> <PERSON> Lush </PERSON>, from the <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francis </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Yacht </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Club </ORGANIZATION>, where Thursday's Child will berth after reaching the finish line marked by the Golden Gate bridge. The racer reported by radio at midday Thursday it was 300 miles south of the Golden Gate, making only 6 knots in unfavorable winds, she said. The 60-foot, 10-ton state-of-the-art racing sloop entered <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> waters before dawn. If it made the Golden Gate by Friday, Thursday's Child would crack the 1854 mark set by the clipper Flying Cloud by 10 days. But the support group estimated that at the current rate, the arrival probably would be on Saturday. The three-member crew, who left <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> on Nov. 23, closed in on the world's oldest existing speed record, duplicating a 14,500-mile passage around fearsome <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Horn </LOCATION> at the tip of <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>. The legendary three-masted Flying Cloud made the journey in 89 days, 8 hours. After hitting gale-force winds up to 40 knots earlier in the day, Thursday's Child apparently hit shifting winds to the north, forcing it into a time consuming tacking drill across the wind in order to continue north, said <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Black </PERSON>, part of the boat's ground support. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said the three crewmen were all well. They are skipper <PERSON> Courtney </PERSON> <PERSON> Hazleton </PERSON>, 32; owner and master <PERSON> Warren </PERSON> <PERSON> Luhrs </PERSON>, 44, and <PERSON> Lars </PERSON> <PERSON> Bergstrom </PERSON>, 54, who helped design the vessel, which features the latest in push-button satellite navigation equipment. Earlier this week <PERSON> Hazleton </PERSON> called the adventure `` some of the finest sailing I ever had. I would do it again at the drop of a hat.'' Even if Thursday's Child succeeds in breaking the record, the vessel's mark may be vanquished before it can even be written in the history books. <PERSON> Black </PERSON> said three other boats are now at sea trying to better Thursday Child's time. The merchantman Flying Cloud, with its 17-story masts that could carry 35 sails, was the marvel of its day. It was reputed the fastest of thousands of sailing vessels that raced each other across the <LOCATION> Atlantic </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Pacific </LOCATION>, often with perishable cargoes.
