<HEAD>Former Minister Leaves Grilling Without Egg on Her Face</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Former junior health minister <PERSON> Edwina </PERSON> <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> emerged smiling Wednesday from a grilling by fellow lawmakers over her remark that most British egg production was affected by food poisoning bacteria. `` She stonewalled every question and acted like a grande dame,'' said lawmaker <PERSON> Ann </PERSON> <PERSON> Winterton </PERSON>, a fellow <ORGANIZATION> Conservative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> member, after the session of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Select </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Agriculture. For nearly eight weeks Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> resisted the committee's summons to appear before it to explain her remark which outraged poultry farmers and led to tons of unsold eggs In an off-the-cuff remark in a brief TV interview she said: `` Most of the egg production in this country, sadly, is now infected with salmonella.'' Her notorious words came during a scare over dangers from eating eggs, when one possible cause of infection mentioned was bad feed given to chickens. As farmers filed lawsuits against the government seeking compensation, Prime Minister <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Thatcher </PERSON> ordered Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> to resign nine days before Christmas. Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> told the committee she had n't meant that most eggs were affected by salmonella bacteria, as one committee member suggested. She said that was a misrepresentation by the media. Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON> said she still believed that a significant number of birds in a significant number of laying flocks were infected. So many eggs were eaten every day that even if only a small proportion of them were affected by the bacteria, they amounted to a very large number, she said. Mrs. <PERSON> Currie </PERSON>, 42, showed up before the bipartisan committee after it threatened to force a House of Commons motion compelling her to appear. The Times of <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> said this procedure was last used 350 years ago. The government is paying out nearly nearly $ 7 million in compensation for 108 million eggs destroyed and some 450,000 slaughtered chickens. It also launched an $ 865,000 advertising campaign to reassure people they could eat eggs without fear _ although it was best to hard-boil them for little children, the elderly and the sick.
