<FIRST>a i AM-Japan-NewCenters Adv16   02-09 0881</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Japan-New Centers, Adv 16,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv16</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Thu AMs, Feb. 16, and Thereafter</HEAD>
<HEAD>New Centers Sprouting in Japan as Tokyo Fills to Its Limits</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID THURBER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OSAKA, Japan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Japanese are beginning to look away from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> as the nation's power center and toward places like <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> or <LOCATION> Kumamoto </LOCATION> in the far-off south for new development and economic influence. The new thrust: <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> is not just <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. For many Japanese now crammed into the capital city, it could mean a return to their roots in the countryside for good jobs and less stressful living. Here in the heart of this industrial city a dozen new skycrapers tower over the <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Castle </LOCATION>, a 400-year-old landmark, casting their shadow on a serene historic site but at the same time looming as a new symbol of decentralization in <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. The complex, called <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> Business Park, is one of dozens of large-scale development projects launched by local business groups in a campaign to reverse the flow of economic power to <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Not only mighty regional centers like <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> but smaller and more remote towns also have begun their own development projects that are luring high-tech industry and beckoning their talented offspring home from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. One such place is <LOCATION> Kumamoto </LOCATION>, 560 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>, about as far away from the capital as you can get without leaving <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> proper. It is the first of 26 locations designated as a `` technopolis'' by the <ORGANIZATION> Ministry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Internatinal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>. The model city there already has research facilities and is to be expanded to encompass two cities, 12 towns and two villages and cover nearly 40 square miles. It's tranquil, `` affluent and easy-going'' says <PERSON> Morihiro </PERSON> <PERSON> Hosokawa </PERSON>, the local governor. It also has an abundance of flat, cheap land. The area already has persuaded major corporations like <ORGANIZATION> Honda </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Matsushita </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> to set up branch offices. It is also the home of <ORGANIZATION> Kyushu </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> NEC </ORGANIZATION>, which claims to be the world's largest producer of integrated circuits. For decades, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> has been at the pinnacle of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s highly centralized society, drawing much of the best the nation had to offer. But as its concentration of political power and its growing role as a world financial center stretch its physical and spiritual limits, more Japanese are beginning to think the capital's dominance should be reduced. Planners also warn that another earthquake in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> like the one that killed 143,000 people in 1923 could devastate the country's centralized infrastructure and severely damage both the Japanese and world economies <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s business and industrial center before World War II, is in the western <LOCATION> Kansai </LOCATION> region about 250 miles southwest of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Community and business leaders there have begun a massive development program for the region of more than 13.5 million people. The project calls for the building of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s first 24-hour international airport, a <ORGANIZATION> Kansai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Science </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> City </ORGANIZATION> for students, researchers and their families, and the <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> and Pacific Trade Center, planned with the hope of displacing <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> as a major distribution center for <LOCATION> Asia </LOCATION> once the British colony reverts to Chinese rule in 1997. By the year 2000, direct investment in the projects will total at least $ 122 billion, analysts say, with indirect investment possibly doubling that figure. During <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s postwar rush to reindustrialize, few questioned <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s dominance. With the best schools, jobs and entertainment, <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> drew millions who dreamed of better lives as well as hundreds of companies wanting to be near government agencies, banks, financial markets and up-to-date information. As a result, more power has become concentrated in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> than in almost any other single city in the world. Thirty million people live in the greater <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> metropolitan area _ a quarter of <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'s population crowded into 2 percent of its area _ triggering the highest land prices in the world; choice commerical real estate was selling for $ 6.7 billion an acre last year. For those unable to afford to live in <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION> itself, commuting to work can take more than four hours a day. While <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>'s attraction still has n't faded, people in rural areas and cities like <LOCATION> Osaka </LOCATION> have begun emphasizing their own local strengths and diversity. `` Cultural and technological over-centralization is dangerous, and if we do n't do something about it, it's likely to create cracks in our society,'' says <PERSON> Kazuro </PERSON> <PERSON> Kuriyama </PERSON>, head of research for the <ORGANIZATION> Kansai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federation </ORGANIZATION>, a grouping of <ORGANIZATION> Kansai </ORGANIZATION> businesses. For many Japanese, regional revitalization means a return to traditional values at a time when so many people no longer live with their relatives or in their hometowns. Towns are reviving and promoting local festivals, crafts and delicacies, while TV shows such as `` Rediscover <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'' and `` Wonderful Trip Around <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>'' introduce the lifestyle and customs of local communities. Beer companies are introducing `` local flavor'' brews designed to appeal to local pride and taste, and the post office plans to release a new series of regional stamps. Even the national government is encouraging a shift away from <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>. Prime Minister <PERSON> Noboru </PERSON> <PERSON> Takeshita </PERSON> has said the government will distribute 100 million yen -LRB- $ 800,000 -RRB- to each of 3,200 or so villages, towns and cities for use in improvement projects. The Cabinet also is moving 79 secondary government bodies out of <LOCATION> Tokyo </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Thu AMs, Feb. 16</NOTE>
