<FIRST>a e AM-APArts:Collins Adv14   02-09 0740</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AP Arts: Collins, Adv 14,0758</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv 14</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Tues AMs, Feb 14 and Thereafter</HEAD>
<BYLINE>A Solo ``Shirley'' Heads For Broadway</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>By MATT WOLF</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Pauline </PERSON> <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> is Broadway-bound in a solo play that took <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> by storm last winter, but it's a mixed blessing for the British actress to go it alone in a foreign country. `` The sad thing is, you've got no one to nudge from the stage and say, ` Is n't this good or bad or whatever,''' said the lone performer in <PERSON> Willy </PERSON> <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>,'' opening Feb. 16 at the Booth Theater. On the plus side, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> is appearing in material she admires, a luxury not always available to actors. `` First of all, I really love the play; I left -LRB- the <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> run -RRB- feeling I had n't had enough,'' said the actress, best-known to Americans as <PERSON> Sarah </PERSON>, the downstairs maid in the popular British TV series `` Upstairs, Downstairs.'' Written by the author of `` Educating Rita'' and the current <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> musical `` Blood Brothers,'' `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>'' is a lengthy, essentially comic soliloquy about a bored Liverpudlian housewife who at age 42 decides to do something about her `` unused life.'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> emphasized that `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>'' is more than a series of barbed, knowing one-liners. `` This is a play. That's the extraordinary thing about it,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said over coffee in the spacious north <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> home she shares with her husband, actor <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Alderton </PERSON>, and their three children. `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>'' premiered in 1986 in <PERSON> Russell </PERSON>'s native <ORGANIZATION> Liverpool </ORGANIZATION>, with local actress <PERSON> Noreen </PERSON> <PERSON> Kershaw </PERSON>. It opened on <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>'s commercial West End last January, winning <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> the best actress award from <ORGANIZATION> Drama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Magazine </ORGANIZATION> and a nomination for this year's <PERSON> Laurence </PERSON> <PERSON> Olivier </PERSON> Awards A separate production opened in <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION>, on Dec. 30. In the fall, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> beat out such candidates as <PERSON> Cher </PERSON> to repeat the part in the movie version with added characters played by <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Conti </PERSON> and <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON>. Due for release next September, it is directed by <PERSON> Lewis </PERSON> <PERSON> Gilbert </PERSON>, who filmed `` Educating <PERSON> Rita </PERSON>.'' The $ 750,000 Broadway production is being staged by its <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> director, <PERSON> Simon </PERSON> <PERSON> Callow </PERSON>, the British movie and stage actor -LRB- `` A Room With a View,'' `` Amadeus'' -RRB- making his <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> directorial debut. <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, who grew up near <LOCATION> Liverpool </LOCATION>, is confident that the British references and phrases in `` Shirley Valentine'' wo n't limit its appeal. `` There's always that which is undone in all of us, that little bit more you ought to do,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said of <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON>'s dilemma, as the character takes solace from drudgery in her wit and dreams of escape. The role is partly a lighter variant of <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>' previous West End assignment, replacing <PERSON> Julia </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON> as the anguished middle-class housewife in <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Ayckbourn </PERSON>'s `` Woman in Mind.'' But she feels `` <PERSON> Shirley </PERSON> <PERSON> Valentine </PERSON>'' has helped widen her acting range. `` It allowed me to move into an area closer to my own age, because I think when you have a round face, you tend to be caught in a peculiar nebulous youth for a long time,'' said <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, dark shoulder-length hair framing her full cheeks. `` Because of the way the world is moving now, there's a greater interest, and indeed a greater market, for plays about middle-aged people,'' said <PERSON> Collins </PERSON>, 48, who spent years playing pert and youthful comic leads in such vehicles as <PERSON> Oscar </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilde </PERSON>'s `` The Importance of Being Earnest'' and <PERSON> Bernard </PERSON> <PERSON> Slade </PERSON>'s `` Romantic Comedy.'' `` There are a lot of middle-aged people about with money to spend who want to see themselves on screen and stage and even as models.'' Television roles occupy much of her time. In the spring, she and her husband will appear in six one-hour episodes of a new show, `` Forever Green,'' about a <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> couple who uproot to the country. Frequent collaborators, the couple were seen on American TV in the show `` No, Honestly,'' but they resisted offers to remake the series appearing as two Americans. Facing her first Broadway appearance, <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> knows the stakes are high. `` The line between success and failure is very much stronger there; you're either a success, or you ai n't,'' she said. But she is philosophical about the much-vaunted power of the <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> critics. `` There's no point wasting energy worrying about that,'' <PERSON> Collins </PERSON> said. `` All I can do is put the best I can into it and hope they like it. If they do n't, then presumably their power will close it, so I wo n't be suffering too long.''
