<HEAD>As GM Shrinks, Main Street Pinched</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Grniet is cq in 28th graf; this story also on financial wires</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BX8 of Feb. 7</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN COOPERMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FRAMINGHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 When <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Motors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> idles its sprawling assembly plant here in August, one of the main engines driving this <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> town's economy will shift into neutral. About 1,200 employees already are on furlough, and 2,000 more will be laid off. <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> will lose its largest employer, which last year paid $ 830,000 in local taxes, spent $ 19 million with local suppliers and had a payroll of $ 59 million. <PERSON> Sharon </PERSON> <PERSON> McWey </PERSON>, a 28-year-old single mother who earned $ 13.18 an hour at the plant, wonders who will pay the bills if she or her 5-year-old daughter gets sick. <PERSON> Leonard </PERSON> <PERSON> Milo </PERSON>, owner of a <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> hardware store, worries he may have to lay off some of his 11 employees. `` One thing affects the next,'' he said. `` You ca n't keep everyone on when you're losing a customer that did $ 100,000 worth of business.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> says the troubled plant, which has gone through at least five shutdowns since 1977, may one day reopen. But industry analysts doubt it, and many workers no longer can tolerate the on-again-off-again nature of the operation. The same painful uncertainty is felt in <LOCATION> Leeds </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Norwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>, and other communities nationwide where the No. 1 automaker has been reducing production capacity for the first time in its 80-year history. <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>, which has suffered a steady erosion in its share of the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car market over the past several years, announced last April that it would start closing plants in an effort to bring capacity into line with sales. The reaction on Wall Street has been enthusiastic; <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION>'s stock rose $ 1.25 to $ 73.375 a share on the day of the announcement and has since climbed to about $ 93. But the impact on Main Street has been severe. `` Talk to any shop owner, any pizza place, any package store in this town,'' said <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mercer </PERSON>, a 34-year-old Framingham native who worked at the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> plant for four years. `` It's not just the 3,000 jobs. It's a whole domino effect.'' <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> says the 40-year-old <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> plant is one of four in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> making <ORGANIZATION> Buick </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Centurys </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Oldsmobile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cutlass </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cieras </ORGANIZATION>, all of which have been running at well below capacity. Eliminating <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> says, will make the other three _ in <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ste </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Therese </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Quebec </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Ramos </PERSON> <PERSON> Aripze </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION> _ more efficient. <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, meanwhile, is feeling recriminations. Some workers blame Local 422 of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Auto </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> for refusing to agree to work-rule changes that might have saved the plant and their jobs. Some union activists accuse executives of mismanaging the plant. If there is a consensus, though, it is that the plant's fate was sealed on a single night two years ago _ June 17, 1986 _ when <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> asked for a zoning change to allow the 54-acre facility to expand and build plastic-body mini-vans. <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>, population 65,100, calls itself `` the largest town in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>,'' because it is the largest community still run by an old-fashioned <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> England </LOCATION> town meeting. With the <ORGANIZATION> Yankee </ORGANIZATION> independence that town meetings are known for, residents peppered <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> officials that June night with questions about noxious emissions, storage of plastic resins and truck traffic. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanscom </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>'s director of public works, remembers the answers as incomplete and the <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> officials as haughty. `` It appeared they thought they were above questions,'' he said. After a lengthy debate, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> fell three votes short, 69-39, of the two-thirds majority needed for a zoning change. This month, the automaker began retooling its <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Tarrytown </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.Y. </LOCATION>, plant to make the plastic mini-vans originally slated for <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION>. On Feb. 1, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> announced that the <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> facility would shut down indefinitely because `` it does not have any new product to manufacture.'' Some residents saw the announcement as spiteful. But the president of the local <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Michelle </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> Flaherty </PERSON>, said the town has only itself to blame. `` What infuriates me is that this plant had a product two years ago that would have ensured its continuation into the 1990s, and the town turned it down,'' she said. `` That's something we have to face up to.'' In other moves to reduce manufacturing capacity last year, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> laid off 4,000 workers at a Firebird-Camaro factory in <LOCATION> Norwood </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; 2,500 at a stamping plant in <LOCATION> Hamilton </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION>; 2,350 at a Fiero plant in <LOCATION> Pontiac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION>; and 1,300 at a Buick-Oldsmobile-Cadillac facility in <LOCATION> Leeds </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mo </LOCATION>. Even with those closings, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> still has excess capacity and probably will have to shut at least two more plants to meet its stated goal of using 100 percent of its <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> car-making capacity by 1992, said <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Grady </PERSON>, an analyst with <ORGANIZATION> Integrated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Automotive </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Wayne </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>. Framingham may be better off than some other affected communities, because it has a diverse economic base that includes computer manufacturing, stationery making and a 375-room hotel In addition, the unemployment rate in <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, at 3.3 percent, is the lowest of any major industrial state. To help workers exploit job opportunities in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> area, <ORGANIZATION> GM </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> UAW </ORGANIZATION> have opened a retraining center, and Gov. <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dukakis </PERSON> has announced a $ 250,000 state grant to help fund it. The <LOCATION> Framingham </LOCATION> plant reopened in May, after a November 1987 shutdown that put 3,700 out of work. When it reopened, more than 1,000 workers with 20 years or more of experience were among those called back. Hopes began anew. `` Because there have been so many layoffs, the perception in everyone's mind is that, ` I'll get called back,''' said <PERSON> Arthur </PERSON> <PERSON> T. </PERSON> <PERSON> Grniet </PERSON>, a 24-year veteran of the plant, after the latest layoff announcement. But some workers, frustrated by the recurring layoffs and startups that afflict the auto industry, are trying to ensure that the coming shutdown is the last they have to endure. `` I know I'm going to make less money and everything,'' said <PERSON> Julio </PERSON> <PERSON> Goncalves </PERSON>, 42, who was laid off and recalled four times in nine years at the plant. `` But enough is enough. I've got to find another job and get on with my life. ... Even if they reopen again, I do n't think if I'm going to come back.
</TEXT>
