<SECOND>BC-Afghan-Uncertainty, Adv 00,0906</SECOND>
<HEAD>$Adv00</HEAD>
<HEAD>For Release Anytime</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Soviets Gone, Afghanistan Faces New Struggle for Power</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Part of a package of Afgahn War stories for release anytime.
Items already moved are BC-Afghan Adventure, b0796; BC-Afghan-Toll, b0797;
BC-Afghan-Quotes, b0798, BC-Afghan-Future, b0799, which moved Feb. 7, and
BC-Afghan-US, b0502 of Feb. 8.</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY RENFREW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Moslem guerrillas who have been fighting the Afghan communist regime are deeply divided, with widely differing visions of the kind of government and nation they want to build. The seven main Afghan guerrilla groups and dozens of small or splinter groups range from moderate traditionalists sympathetic to the old <LOCATION> Afghan </LOCATION> monarchy to fundamentalist Islamic revolutionaries. But the main problem, most leaders say, is who will come to power after the expected fall of the communist regime now that the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> has pulled its forces out of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>. `` There is much hope, but there is also much doubt about the future of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' said <PERSON> Masoud </PERSON> <PERSON> Khalili </PERSON>, a senior guerrilla, in one of a series of interviews with The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> invasion was the greatest challenge in Afghan history,'' said <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Hadi </PERSON> <PERSON> Arghandewhal </PERSON>, another guerrilla official. `` Now there is an equal challenge to rebuild <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>,'' Rival guerrilla groups have clashed in the past and show no sign of mending their divisions despite an outward show of unity. Several guerrilla groups reportedly have been stockpiling weapons for years for use in any internal struggle for power. The guerrillas say they agree on forming a democratic <ORGANIZATION> Islamic </ORGANIZATION> government under an elected head of state and legislature. Beyond that broad outline, they are vague. `` We want to make everyone a part of the future, but not everyone can be a -LRB- government -RRB- minister,'' said <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Haq </PERSON>, a guerrilla military commander. Many Afghans dismiss suggestions that they will wind up with a radical Islamic state comparable to the one Shiite Moslems created in neighboring <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>. Most Afghans belong to the rival Sunni sect. But moderate Afghans fear the future may hold little toleration for different or modern ideas if some of the more radical guerrilla organizations control any future government. `` Afghans are Moslems, but most do not want to live under a government that tells them how to live or how religious they must be,'' said one Afghan exile. Any struggle for power will be complicated by <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s historic disunity and instability The nation is deeply divided between ethnic, tribal, linguistic and religious groups that have competed for power for centuries. Past Afghan governments exerted little real control outside the cities and large towns. A major task in rebuilding <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> now will be finding ways to ease the divisions and promote a common sense of nationalism or face chronic feuding, guerrilla leaders say. `` This is a major problem that the war has made worse. We must solve it, but we can not do it with slogans,'' said <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Rahim </PERSON>, a guerrilla official. A prolonged struggle for power could erupt between the rival guerrilla parties, the many different ethnic and regional groups and the semi-autonomous guerrilla military commanders who actually control many parts of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>, according to some analysts. `` Civil war is possible if the leaders do not come up with a solution to <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s problems,'' <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> could be divided into small, warring states under rival guerrilla commanders in the same way <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> was broken up among rival power groups, analysts say. Any central government in <LOCATION> Kabul </LOCATION>, the capital, would be as ineffective and divided as the <LOCATION> Lebanese </LOCATION> government, they said. `` I hope <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> will become like <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION> after the war, not like <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>,'' <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> said. The thousands of guerrillas from rival groups must be disarmed to ensure the restoration of stability and allow construction of an effective civilian government, Afghan analysts say. But they add that it will be hard to persuade guerrillas who have fought for years to surrender their weapons and power, especially when there will be few jobs or other rewards in the desperately poor nation. `` We must succeed with the pen as we succeeded with the gun,'' <PERSON> Haq </PERSON> said. `` The mujahedeen -LRB- Islamic holy warriors -RRB- must go school, the people must go back to farming. It will not be easy.'' Other guerrilla officials say Afghans are exhausted from a decade of war and would turn against any of the guerrilla groups that start a struggle for power. But only the main guerrilla groups, they acknowledge, have military power. The threat of chaos and disunity will increase if <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION>'s neighbors and the superpowers compete for influence in the country, guerrilla officials and analysts say <LOCATION> Pakistan </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, which armed and backed the guerrillas, hope a new government will be friendly to them. At the same time, the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION> is likely to be troubled by a government unfriendly to it. <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION> also wants a voice in the future of <LOCATION> Afghanistan </LOCATION> to counter <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> and Pakistani influence in the strategic nation. Iranian-supported Afghan Shiite guerrillas also are also expected to seek a strong voice in a future Islamic government despite opposition from Sunni guerrilla groups, who are in the majority. `` We must remember that we are all Afghans. Only that way can we solve our problems,'' said <PERSON> Khalili </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
