 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> said he expects many banks to acquire thrifts under the government's savings industry rescue plan, but he does n't believe the program signals the death of the industry <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON> also told a meeting of international bankers Wednesday that the government actively would seek restitution from fraudulent thrift barons, whose actions have contributed to the industry's losses, said to be accruing at $ 500 million a month. He said the $ 90 billion bailout plan announced this week by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> does not signal the demise of a financial institution created in the 1930s to help Americans buy single-family homes.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is proposing to rescue the savings and loan industry with a 30-year, $ 200 billion financing plan that would ease the pain in his administration and shift the cost to the future. In fact, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, despite proposing the biggest government bailout ever, will achieve an immediate $ 200 million savings in the 1990 budget he submits to <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> on Thursday, making it easier to keep his `` no new taxes'' pledge in his first budget. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would spend only $ 1.9 billion in tax dollars in 1990, compared with $ 2.1 billion proposed by the outgoing <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration. <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called for outlays of $ 18.5 billion in fiscal years 1990 through 1993, $ 3.1 billion more than <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would spend in his first four budgets.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>FRESNO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The arctic cold wave that blew through <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> this week sent shivers through the state's multimillion-dollar floral and citrus industries, ruining part of the lemon crop and possibly boosting the price of a Valentine bouquet As the weather moderated in the state's major growing regions Wednesday, growers assessed the cold-caused damage by slicing open lemons and eyeing rows of drooping carnations.
