 Stock prices were little changed, bogging down after Tuesday's advance that carried the market to new post-crash highs The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials closed with a 3.93 loss at 2,343.21. The dollar edged narrowly lower against several major currencies Wednesday as traders appeared reluctant to speculate on currency shifts in advance of President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s budget address Thursday. Bond prices mostly fell, reflecting trader disappointment with a lack of buying interest in the federal government's debt-refinancing auction of $ 9.5 billion in 10-year notes. Cattle futures settled narrowly mixed in cautious trading prior to release of a report on the nation's cattle herds. Soybean futures were down sharply; precious metals advanced; energy futures retreated; and gold and silver futures strengthened.
