<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> erroneously reported the length of an average movie in a story about the 100th anniversary of <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>'s motion-picture film products. The average movie, at 90 feet of film a minute, is about about 9,000 to 12,000 feet long. <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> estimates filmmakers use at least 20 times more negative film than the finished product requires, which means an average movie might use 180,000 to 240,000 feet of film. If 1,000 prints are needed, a studio must buy 9 million feet to 12 million feet of print film.
