<SECOND>PM-Steel Talks, Bjt,0579</SECOND>
<HEAD>USW Wants Early Negotiations With Steel Industry</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Steelworkers </LOCATION> officials say they will ask four major steelmakers for an early start to contract negotiations and will demand a share of the industry's renewed profits when the talks begin. `` Our people have made great sacrifices for a great many years. We might as well get at it,'' <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> President <PERSON> Lynn </PERSON> <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said Wednesday. Contracts covering about 43,700 union members are due to expire July 31 at <ORGANIZATION> Bethlehem </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Inland </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industries </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the third - through sixth-largest producers respectively `` We're prepared to meet on a schedule that's mutually satisfactory,'' said <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION> spokesman <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Von </PERSON> <PERSON> Spreckelsen </PERSON>. The union has agreed to two consecutive rounds of contract concessions since 1983. `` Our members are working in 1989 for 1982 wage rates at best,'' the <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> said in a 36-page statement approved by a 400-member strategy committee. The <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> will negotiate separately but concurrently with the companies. The talks will cover 20,500 workers at <LOCATION> Bethlehem </LOCATION>, 11,600 at Inland, 7,000 at National and 4,700 at <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> represents only a portion of the workers at <ORGANIZATION> Armco </ORGANIZATION>. The contract with the largest producer, <ORGANIZATION> USX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, runs to early 1991. Second-ranked <ORGANIZATION> LTV </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Wheeling-Pittsburgh </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Steel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> both are in Chapter 11 reorganization and will negotiate when they emerge from bankruptcy court. `` Our union's fundamental goal is ... to raise the standard of living for our members in every possible way by negotiating improved income, cost-of-living protection, better benefits and working conditions and more secure employment,'' the committee statement said. After losing $ 12 billion from 1982-86, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> steel industry made profits of more than $ 3 billion in 1987-88 and is expecting another good year in 1989. `` Our members have made an enormous contribution to the success of the industry,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. `` The success they've had should be justly and fairly shared with our members.'' He said union negotiators will emphasize a basic wage increase over profit sharing. `` They're entitled to have some guaranteed improvement'' in pay, <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. The union also wants restrictions on mandatory overtime and the hiring of non-union contractors. <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said all the companies are requiring excessive overtime rather than hiring additional employees, which increases pension and benefit expenses. `` We think that's wrong,'' he said. The companies' claim that overtime is necessary because skilled workers are not readily available is `` a reflection of the failure of the industry to maintain its training and apprentice programs,'' <PERSON> Williams </PERSON> said. For similar reasons, non-union contractors are used to maintain equipment and clean plants, he said. <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> attorneys said they've found cases where companies have contracted for janitorial services at $ 50 to $ 70 per hour and maintenance services at $ 75 to $ 100 per hour when <ORGANIZATION> USW </ORGANIZATION> members could have done the work for half as much or less. `` Some of these prices blow your mind,'' said chief Counsel <PERSON> Bernie </PERSON> <PERSON> Kleiman </PERSON>. According to <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> figures released by the union, from December 1982 to October 1988 the average hourly earnings of steelworkers, including overtime earnings, rose 2.5 percent, from $ 14.40 to $ 14.76, while those of coal miners rose 20.8 percent, from $ 13.20 to $ 15.95, oil refinery workers rose 22.2 percent, from $ 13.49 to $ 16.49, and auto workers rose 24 percent, from $ 12.98 to $ 16.09.
