<HEAD>Philippines Opposes Mediation Of Nuclear Plant Suit Against Westinghouse</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HELEN J. SIMON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> says <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> wants to cover up alleged bribes to her predecessor by using an international body to secretly settle a lawsuit over a $ 2.3 billion nuclear plant. `` Defendants ... do n't want a public accounting in their own country,'' Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> said Wednesday in a statement issued through the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>. `` They would rather have a secret arbitration in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> where evidence of their action would be kept secret.'' The <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> filed court papers Wednesday in <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> District </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> here opposing arbitration. In December, the <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> government sued <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary and plant designer <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <ORGANIZATION> Roe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Enterprises </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>, an Oradell-based engineering firm. The government says the contract for the nuclear power plant should be canceled because of allegations that bribes were paid to former President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>. Other allegations include substandard work and construction of the plant, located on the <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Peninsula </LOCATION> about 60 miles west of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>, near an earthquake fault. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> says the lawsuit is politically motivated and that independent analysts have verified the safety of the 620-megawatt plant, which was completed in the final months of the <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> administration in 1985 but never put into operation. In mid-December, it filed a motion asking <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Court Judge <PERSON> Dickinson </PERSON> <PERSON> Debevoise </PERSON> to stay the lawsuit pending arbitration by the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chamber </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Geneva </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>. In its 70-page memorandum, the <ORGANIZATION> Phillipines </ORGANIZATION> says a contract clause calling for an arbritrator to resolve differences between the plant builders and the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> is invalid because the state-run <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Power </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corporation </ORGANIZATION> was forced to sign the agreement although it opposed it. `` Rather than competing for the project on the merits, the defendants conspired together to pay multimillion dollar bribes for the benefit of former President <PERSON> Ferdinand </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to assure they were awarded the contracts for work on the project,'' the memorandum says. The payments were allegedly arranged through <PERSON> Herminio </PERSON> <PERSON> Disini </PERSON>, who was married to the first cousin of <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' wife, <PERSON> Imelda </PERSON>, and wired to secret Swiss bank accounts, it said. `` We deal here with a criminal scheme of bribery, graft and fraud carried out by the defendants at the highest level of the Philippine government,'' the document says. `` It is this criminal scheme that invalidates the arbitration clauses upon which the defendants base their motions.'' <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> officials, who said they only briefly reviewed the new documents, said they contained no new information. `` They are trying to avoid arbitration ... by saying there was some type of fraud,'' <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Briskman </PERSON> said. `` There is no evidence showing fraud by <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION>.'' The memorandum was accompanied by four volumes of evidence documenting the government's claims. Although the volumes were not immediately available, a statement from <ORGANIZATION> Philippine </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> Secretary <PERSON> Sedfrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> said they included over a dozen sworn statements from top <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> officials opposing the construction of the plant, including the head of the power corporation. Also included are statements from a former <PERSON> Burns </PERSON> and <PERSON> Roe </PERSON> executive and <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> sales representative who allegedly participated in the scheme, and documents seized in <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> after <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> fled the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> said. `` The <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION> documents prove that President <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON>' favoring of <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> at the expense of the government and <ORGANIZATION> NPC </ORGANIZATION> was not disinterested, but was done by <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> to protect his financial stake in the transaction,'' <PERSON> Ordonez </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Marcos </PERSON> has since been indicted on unrelated federal racketeering charges in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> but has not appeared before the court due to illness. <ORGANIZATION> Westinghouse </ORGANIZATION> plans to file a response in March, continuing to push for arbitration, and the judge is expected to make his ruling sometime after that, <PERSON> Briskman </PERSON> said.
