<HEAD>Audi Loses In Car-Owner's Appeal Of Product Liability Case Involving
5000's</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT WADE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A product-liability judgment that requires <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> America </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> to pay $ 100,000 in damages for acceleration problems with its <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000 is another public relations setback for the automaker, an analyst says. A three-judge panel of the <ORGANIZATION> Appellate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Division </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Superior </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> on Wednesday reinstated a lower court jury verdict that awarded punitive damages to <PERSON> Germaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON>, of <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>. She was injured along with her three children when an <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> 5000 smashed through their apartment in 1983. The car's driver, <PERSON> Harold </PERSON> <PERSON> Horowitz </PERSON> of <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON>, told police the automobile lunged forward suddenly. Ms. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON>' attorney, <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Hely </PERSON>, said the ruling demonstrates <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>'s liability for a design defect. Auto industry analyst <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Drexel </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Burnham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Lambert </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> said the ruling only adds to public relations problems for <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>, which has been dealt poor sales reports because of an unintended acceleration case it eventually won. `` The monthly sales numbers for Audis have been dismal since all of the publicity around the unintended acceleration arose last year,'' <PERSON> Healy </PERSON> said. He said <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION>'s <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> sales were 60,000 cars in 1986, 41,000 cars in 1987 and 23,000 cars in 1988. Ms. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON>' attorney shared <PERSON> Healy </PERSON>'s belief that the ruling was poor for public relations. `` Because the truth comes out in this opinion about how they covered up and how they made a correction that was obvious they had to make, it really reflects terribly on the company and how they handled this matter,'' <PERSON> Hely </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Hely </PERSON> had contended in lower court arguments that <ORGANIZATION> Audi </ORGANIZATION> knew the accelerator and brake pedals were put too close together and sometimes caused drivers to step on both simultaneously, prompting the car to lunge forward. A civil jury last March decided <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> was responsible for the design problem, awarding Ms. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> $ 100,000 in punitive damages and $ 14,000 in compensatory damages. But Superior Court Judge <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON> sided with company attorneys and set aside the higher award, finding there was no proof <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> knew the car had problems and failed to correct them. The appeals court's 16-page decision reverses <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON>. In January, Ms. <PERSON> Gibbs </PERSON> asked the appeals court to reinstate the punitive award, while <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> simultaneously asked the appeals court to also set aside the $ 14,000 award. The company said the appeals court opinion is directed only at the lower court judge's discretionary powers. `` The appellate court apparently based its decision on the feeling that the judge in the lower court had abused his discretion. We disagree with that,'' said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON>, a spokesman for <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Troy </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Mich. </LOCATION> `` We feel the judge acted within his discretionary rights and we are looking very carefully to see what additional remedies we might have,'' he said. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> told the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Highway </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Traffic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> in 1983 that it would take corrective measures to `` prevent inadvertent activation of brake and gas pedals at the same time,'' according to court papers <PERSON> Hely </PERSON> filed in arguing the case last month. Internal <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> documents and a government report conclude the car would lunge when the accelerator and brake pedal were pressed simultaneously, and the pedals were arranged close enough that the accelerator often is applied when the driver tries to brake, <PERSON> Hely </PERSON> said. The documents show <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> knew as early as 1979 of the defect. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> declined to comment about the internal documents filed by <PERSON> Hely </PERSON>, saying they were not properly introduced because they were not authenticated. <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> attorney <PERSON> Chuck </PERSON> <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON> said <PERSON> McKenzie </PERSON> improperly allowed introduction of the documents, even though it was <PERSON> Dolan </PERSON> who provided them to the court. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> said the company's options include trying to obtain another appeals court hearing. <PERSON> Hely </PERSON> said he expected the appeals court decision to stand, and that the <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> would not grant a motion for the justices to hear the case. <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> stressed that the case did not involve unintended acceleration, which involves the car lunging forward uncontrollably when it is placed in gear.
