<HEAD>Sources: Chicago Board Of Trade Won't Ban Dual Trading</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, in an effort to restore confidence in its ability to regulate itself, is considering a number of changes in trading procedures, sources said. But the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION>, the world's largest commodities exchange, does not intend to stop brokers from making transactions for customers as well as their own account, according to the sources. Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> directors are reviewing other trading practices and have voted to spend $ 1 million to improve the computerized trade-monitoring system, according to people who attended his private, one-hour meeting with members Wednesday. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> also announced during the meeting that the exchange's directors have voted to increase the maximum fine for offenses to $ 250,000 from $ 75,000, the sources told <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> officials have scheduled another membership meeting today, at which they are expected to announce plans to develop a computerized system for after-hours trading. The practice of traders making transactions for customers and dealing for themselves is a controversial one known as dual trading. The <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> directors' unanimous endorsement of dual trading was seen by some as a sign the exchange will not bend to criticism at a time when the futures industry is under intense scrutiny by the <ORGANIZATION> FBI </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> prosecutors. The government has launched a massive investigation into suspected fraud at the <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, and dual trading is one of the practices under examination. The undercover probe, which was disclosed Jan. 19, is tied to allegations that as many as 100 traders and brokers at <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>'s futures exchanges cheated customers out of millions of dollars in executing their orders to buy and sell contracts for future deliveries of commodities, ranging from soybeans to foreign currencies Critics contend that dual trading creates opportunities for unscrupulous traders to cheat customers. But supporters of the practice say it provides a financial incentive for independent traders to work in the exchange's pits, thereby increasing the efficiency of the futures markets. `` I believe in dual trading,'' said one exchange member who spoke only on condition of anonymity. `` I believe it should happen and should continue to happen.'' Commodities exchanges are overseen by the <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a federal agency, but the creation and enforcement of many trading rules is left up to the individual exchanges _ a policy that is favored by <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> leaders. <ORGANIZATION> BOT </ORGANIZATION> officials would not comment publicly on Wednesday's meeting. But one exchange source said privately that some of the exchange's largest users, including agricultural concerns and pension-fund managers, had lobbied in favor of retaining dual trading <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said other trade practices _ including curb trading, in which traders execute a few buy or sell orders after the closing bell _ are under review, sources said. They said <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> told members that the exchange's computerized trade-monitoring system, which creates a minute-by-minute record of trades, was about 95 percent accurate. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said that with scheduled improvements, the system should be able to reconstruct trades with 100 percent accuracy, the sources said.
