<HEAD>Fourth-Quarter Earnings Down 78.8 Percent; Restructuring Cited</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PEGGY ANDERSEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Roebuck </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> reported record fourth-quarter revenue Thursday but a 78.8 percent drop in earnings, attributing the results to one-time costs in the behemoth retailer's fight to spruce up its image <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' earnings of $ 117.4 million, or 32 cents a share, for the three months ended Dec. 31 compared with $ 554.4 million, or $ 1.46 per share, for the century-old company in the year-earlier period. The fourth consecutive quarterly earnings decline was attributed to a $ 500 million outlay for the massive restructuring announced last fall. The company is attempting to streamline and overhaul its market approach to offer low pricing, more contemporary displays and outside brand names. One analyst said he considers the fourth-quarter showing a prelude to a major upswing for the company. `` Sears lacked two ingredients to growth,'' said analyst <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Landschulz </PERSON> with <ORGANIZATION> Cowen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION>. `` One was competitive pricing. The other was a power format _ a really aggressive marketing tool. I think these changes address both these key weaknesses.'' <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> has not yet begun an all-out promotional campaign to alert consumers to its metamorphosis. But <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brennan </PERSON>, company chairman and chief executive officer, also predicted an improved balance sheet, calling 1988 `` a year of major transition.'' The fourth-quarter plunge reflected after-tax accounting charges of $ 442 million for the restructuring of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> and $ 58.6 million for a loss on the sale of <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION>' <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION> group life and health insurance, the company said. Fourth-quarter revenue totaled a record $ 14.56 billion, up 9 percent from $ 13.36 billion for the year-earlier period. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> has said the restructuring includes the planned sale of the landmark <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tower </ORGANIZATION> and Coldwell Bankers commercial real estate subsidiary, plus the buyback of 10 percent of its 380 million outstanding shares. The company said it would concentrate on consumer-oriented businesses _ retailing, insurance, residential real estate and financial services. Before the restructuring charge, the company said, fourth-quarter earnings totaled $ 618 million or $ 1.65 per share. For the year ended Dec. 31, earnings totaled $ 1.45 billion or $ 3.84 per share, 11 percent down from $ 1.63 billion or $ 4.30 per share in 1987. Revenue totaled a record $ 50.25 billion, up 9.5 percent from $ 40.95 billion in 1987. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> said 1988 results include the adoption of new income tax and insurance accounting standards, and discontinuance of <ORGANIZATION> Allstate </ORGANIZATION>'s group life-health operations and <ORGANIZATION> Coldwell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banker </ORGANIZATION>'s commercial division Revenue for all previous periods was restated for the discontinued operations and the new accounting standard, the company said. <ORGANIZATION> Sears </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merchandise </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Group </ORGANIZATION> reported a fourth-quarter loss of $ 113.5 million after the $ 442 million restructuring charge. Before the charge, the group's fourth-quarter income was $ 328.5 million, down from $ 414.9 million in 1987.
