<HEAD>Cattle Futures Crunched By Bearish USDA Report</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 A government report showing a larger-than-expected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cattle herd knocked cattle futures prices to the mat Thursday on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> but analysts were skeptical of the report's accuracy. On other markets, cotton futures prices fell sharply; grains and soybeans were mixed; precious metals futures declined; and energy futures were mixed. Prices for all cattle futures except the February live cattle contract plunged the permitted daily limit of 1 -LCB- cents at the opening bell and stayed limit-down for the rest of the session. The contract for February delivery of live cattle settled 1.40 cents lower at 73.97 cents a pound while the near-month feeder cattle contract, for delivery in March, settled at 82.92 cents a pound. Pork futures prices fell in sympathy with the cattle market. Live hogs finished .50 cent to 1.05 cents lower with February at 41.90 cents a pound; frozen pork bellies were .12 cent to 1.13 cents lower with February at 37.57 cents a pound. The sell-off was triggered by Wednesday's semi-annual <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> cattle inventory report, a head count of the nation's cattle herd. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> reported there were 99.5 million cattle and calves in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> as of Jan. 1, only a few thousand fewer than the previous year. The industry consensus expectation was for the herd to total fewer than 98 million cattle. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report implied that after six years of thinning cattle numbers, producers were starting to rebuild their herds. But many analysts said they did not believe the report, especially its implication of an extremely high birth rate in the second half of 1988. `` We had a 92 percent calving rate, the highest in 15 years, in a year when you had the driest, hottest summer since 1932,'' said <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> O'Hare </PERSON>, an analyst in <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> with <ORGANIZATION> Smith </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Barney </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Harris </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Upham </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ; </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> `` This looks like one of those aberrational things where you've got to wonder what's going on here,'' he said `` There are just too many contrary things to come into -LRB- the report -RRB- to really believe it.'' Analysts said the bulk of the futures selling appeared to have come from speculative commodity funds, not cattle producers or beef processors, possibly an indication that the beef industry also was skeptical of the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> numbers. Cotton futures prices fell sharply on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cotton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> on expectations that another <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> report would be bearish for the cotton market. And so it was. In a monthly supply-demand report issued after the close of trading, the <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> estimated the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> cotton stockpile on Aug. 1 would stand at 9.2 million bales, compared with the January estimate of 8.8 million bales and the Aug. 1, 1988 stockpile of 5.8 million bales. Cotton settled .80 cent to 1.75 cent lower with March at 57.64 cents a pound. Grain and soybean futures were mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> in dull trading ahead of the same <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> supply-demand report. In the report, the government lowered its estimate for 1988-89 Argentine soybean production to 9 million metric tons from 11 million metric tons and lowered its 1988-89 Argentine corn production forecast to 6 million metric tons from 8 million. The <ORGANIZATION> USDA </ORGANIZATION> also lowered its 1988-89 Soviet grain production estimate by 5 million metric tons to 195 million. Analysts interpreted the report as neutral to slightly bullish for grain and soybean futures. Wheat settled 1 -RCB- cents to 3 \ cents lower with March at $ 4.25 \ a bushel; corn was \ cent lower to 1 \ cents higher with March at $ 2.65 a bushel; oats were 1 cent to 3 -LCB- cents lower with March at $ 2.06 a bushel; soybeans were 1 \ cents lower to -RCB- cent higher with March at $ Gold and silver futures retreated modestly in technically-inspired trading on <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. Gold settled $ 1.10 to $ 1.30 lower with April at $ 398 a troy ounce; silver was 2.4 cents to 3 cents lower with March at $ 5.915 a troy ounce. Energy futures prices finished narrowly mixed on the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> in an uneventful session. West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 10 cents lower to 9 cents higher with March at $ 17.39 a barrel; heating oil was .46 cent lower to .27 cent higher with March at 48.61 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was .30 cent to .58 cent lower with March at 48.36 cents a gallon.
