<HEAD>With AM-Eastern-Machinists Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, the nation's largest airline company, reported a $ 224.4 million fourth-quarter loss Thursday, attributing the results to travails that ranged from federal safety probes to labor-management turmoil at its Eastern and <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> subsidiaries. The October-December performance compared with a $ 265.6 million loss in the year-earlier period, and widened the overall 1988 loss to $ 718.6 million _ 54 percent greater than the $ 466.2 million <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> lost in 1987. Miami-based <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> reported losses of $ 101.7 million for the quarter on revenues of $ 844.4 million. That compared with a loss of $ 143.4 million on revenues of $ 1 billion in the same period a year earlier. Houston-based <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> incurred a fourth-quarter loss of $ 99.2 million on revenues of $ 1.1 billion. During the same period in 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 78.8 million on revenues of $ 1.1 billion. Fourth-quarter revenue for the parent company totaled $ 2 billion vs. $ 2.1 billion in the year-earlier quarter. For all of 1988, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> revenue totaled $ 8.6 billion, the same as the year earlier. Eastern lost $ 335.4 million on revenues of $ 3.8 billion for all of 1988. In 1987, <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 181.7 million on revenues of $ 4.4 billion. <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> lost $ 315.5 million on revenues of $ 4.7 billion for all of 1988, vs. a $ 258.1 million loss on revenues of $ 4.1 billion in 1987. In a statement, <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> said the 1988 results `` reflected the numerous and unprecedented challenges faced by both <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION> and Eastern during the past year'' and that future results at the two airlines `` will reflect the fact that these challenges are being successfully met.'' In 1988, both airlines were subject of an unprecedented investigation by the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aviation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION>, which determined the two carriers were run safely. The probe, however, concluded that labor turmoil at Eastern must be defused before it creates risks to passengers. The turmoil intensified this week with <ORGANIZATION> Eastern </ORGANIZATION>'s militant machinists, who were voting on whether to authorize a strike next month. Last week, <ORGANIZATION> Continental </ORGANIZATION>'s president, <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Shugrue </PERSON>, quit after a year on the job, becoming the carrier's sixth former president in as many years.
