<HEAD>Money Supply Measures Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 All three measures of the nation's money supply advanced in late January, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> reported Thursday. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said its narrowest measure of the money supply, M1, rose $ 900 million to a seasonally adjusted $ 787.1 billion in the week ended Jan. 30 from $ 786.2 billion in the previous week. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> said the measure known as M2 rose $ 600 million to a seasonally adjusted $ 3,072.0 billion from $ 3,071.4 billion the previous week. An even broader measure, M3, increased $ 900 million to a seasonally adjusted $ 3,920.6 billion from $ 3,919.7 billion. M1 includes cash in circulation, deposits in checking accounts and non-bank travelers checks. M2 is M1 plus accounts like savings deposits and money-market mutual funds. M3 is M2 plus less-liquid accounts, such as certificates of deposit in minimum denominations of $ 100,000. In judging its monetary policy, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has indicated it is monitoring the value of the dollar, commodity prices and the difference between short - and long-term interest rates It also has shifted its attention from M1 to the two broader money supply measures. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> last year set a provisional target for 1989 of 3 percent to 7 percent growth in M2 and 3.5 percent to 7.5 percent growth in M3. The <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has not set a target for M1 growth since early 1987. For the latest 13 weeks, M2 averaged $ 3,067.8 billion, a 4.3 percent seasonally adjusted annual rate of gain from the previous 13 weeks. M3 averaged $ 3,911.4 billion, up 5.2 percent, while M1 rose 2.0 percent to an average of $ 787.8 billion. In other reports: _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> reported discount window borrowing, exclusing extended credit, averaged $ 698 million a day in the week ended Wednesday, up from $ 263 million in the previous week _ The <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> St. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Louis </ORGANIZATION> reported that the monetary base, the seasonally adjusted total of member bank reserves held at <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> banks and cash in bank vaults and in circulation, was $ 288.0 billion in the two-week period ended Wednesday, down from $ 290.7 billion two weeks earlier
