<HEAD>Federal Probe Spurs Computerization of Futures Industry</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: New throughout to UPDATE with comments from Board of Trade meeting.
Stands for AM-Commodities Probe-Computers on the AM Business News Digest.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> executives informed members Thursday of plans for an electronic trading system that would operate during hours when the trading floor is closed, sources said. Exchange Chairman <PERSON> Karsten </PERSON> <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said the system was designed to give foreign investors easier access to the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s burgeoning market for <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond futures, according to exchange members who attended the closed-door meeting But industry observers said the move into computerized trading by the world's largest futures exchange appeared to be prompted by a federal investigation of suspected fraud at the Board of Trade and the rival <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>. The proposal apparently represents a 180-degree turn in philosophy for the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>, which last fall decried a similar system being developed by the <ORGANIZATION> Chicago </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> as inefficient, prone to abuse and a poor substitute for the traditional `` open-outcry'' method of futures trading. A Board of Trade spokesman said he could not comment on the meeting. One veteran trader who attended the meeting said <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> touted the proposed system as `` the closest thing to the open-outcry system'' and thus superior to the <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> system being developed by the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>. Like <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION>'s system would use a computer to match orders to buy and sell contracts for future deliveries of financial instruments. Also like <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, the system would be open to other futures exchanges that wish to list their products for trading. But unlike <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, which the <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION> is developing in partnership with London-based <ORGANIZATION> Reuters </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> PLC </ORGANIZATION>, the Board of Trade system would be developed and owned entirely by the exchange and its members. The exchange plans to hold several smaller meetings with traders over the next three weeks to explain the system before putting it to a membership vote March 2, according to traders who attended the meeting. <PERSON> Mahlmann </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> would retain its 21-month-old night trading session for <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> bond futures, a successful effort to attract more business from <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Details about the electronic system were sketchy and many traders, who spoke on condition of anonymity, left the meeting confused. `` If the floor vote were held today I do n't think it would pass,'' said one trader. `` Not because people are against it in principle, but there are just too many questions about it.'' Industry observers linked the exchange's change of heart about electronic trading to the recently disclosed investigation of futures trading. `` What this whole scandal has done is to bring up the time when computerization is the norm,'' said <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Siegel </PERSON>, a professor of finance at <ORGANIZATION> Northwestern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Kellogg </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Graduate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Management </ORGANIZATION>. `` As soon as you mechanize, you're removing the human element, and the human element is what this latest furor is all about,'' added <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Whaley </PERSON>, an associate professor and co-director of the Futures and <ORGANIZATION> Options </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> at <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Fuqua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Durham </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.C. </LOCATION> Electronic trading systems use computers to match buy and sell orders. Several foreign futures exchanges already operate such systems. All commodities trading in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> now is done by professional traders who crowd into recessed pits on exchange floors and execute customer orders through a combination of shouts and hand signals. Abuse of this `` open-outcry'' trading method is the apparent target of a <ORGANIZATION> Justice </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> investigation revealed on Jan. 19. Federal authorities reportedly are investigating allegations that as many as 100 traders and brokers systematically cheated customers out of millions of dollars while executing their orders in the futures markets. The <ORGANIZATION> Merc </ORGANIZATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> is seen as a way to make its financial futures markets more convenient for overseas customers. Last September, Board of Trade President <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Donovan </PERSON> urged the federal <ORGANIZATION> Commodity </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Futures </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trading </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> not to approve <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION>, contending in a letter that the proposed system was `` inherently susceptible to manipulation, prearranged trading and other abuses.'' The <ORGANIZATION> CFTC </ORGANIZATION> approved <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> last week. The <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, which trades crude oil and platinum futures, and the <LOCATION> Sydney </LOCATION> Futures Exchange of <LOCATION> Australia </LOCATION> have agreed to list some of their products for <ORGANIZATION> Globex </ORGANIZATION> trading.
